SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Server OS Installation Methods", body:"<p>Objective <strong>2.1</strong> asks you to install server operating systems given a scenario, and the first decision is <em>how</em> the OS reaches the hardware. A <span class='keyterm'>server administrator (sysadmin)</span> rarely walks a DVD to every rack; instead, deployment is engineered for <strong>speed, consistency, and repeatability</strong>. The source files for an OS can arrive on optical media (CD/DVD), a <span class='keyterm'>USB flash drive</span>, across the network, or embedded directly on the appliance by the manufacturer. Embedded installs are common in routers, ATMs, and self-service kiosks where the OS is baked in at the factory rather than installed in the field.</p><h3>Local (Attended) Installation</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>local installation</span> boots the target from removable media and runs the <em>installer</em> interactively. Installers offer a <strong>graphical</strong> (mouse-driven, guided, self-explanatory) path or a <strong>command-line</strong> path (commands typed manually, faster, but assumes knowledge). The installer manages partitioning, file-system selection, a few OS features, and creation of the initial administrator account. Attended installs are fine for one-off builds but are slow and inconsistent at scale because a human answers every prompt.</p><h3>Network / PXE Installation</h3><p>For mass deployment the target boots over the LAN using <span class='keyterm'>PXE (Preboot Execution Environment)</span>. The destination machine has no OS yet, so its NIC firmware requests a boot image via DHCP/TFTP, then pulls the OS source files from a deployment server and executes them. PXE removes the need to physically touch each box and underpins both imaging and unattended workflows.</p><h3>Unattended / Automated Installation</h3><p>An <span class='keyterm'>unattended (automated) installation</span> references an <span class='keyterm'>answer file</span> instead of asking the user. The installer reads partition layout, locale, account info, and feature selections from the file, producing <strong>fast and identical</strong> builds. Microsoft calls automated deployments that bundle patches, drivers, and applications <span class='keyterm'>slipstream</span> installs; in Linux the equivalent answer file is a <span class='keyterm'>Kickstart</span> file. By the time the script finishes, the server is installed, patched, and ready for work.</p><h3>Imaging and Cloud Images</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Imaging</span> is automation by clone. A perfectly configured <em>source computer</em> is captured, uploaded to an <em>imaging server</em>, and pushed to one or more <em>destination servers</em> that come up byte-for-byte identical. VMs take this further: a VM is just a configuration file, so it can be <strong>cloned</strong> or turned into a reusable <span class='keyterm'>template</span> for self-service provisioning. <span class='keyterm'>Cloud images</span> apply the same idea in a CSP — you launch a pre-built marketplace or custom image and a virtual server appears in minutes, fast, consistent, and customizable.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Speed</th><th>Consistency</th><th>Best for</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Local / attended (DVD, USB)</td><td>Slow</td><td>Low</td><td>One-off or repair builds</td></tr><tr><td>Network / PXE</td><td>Fast</td><td>High</td><td>Diskless or bare-metal at scale</td></tr><tr><td>Unattended (answer/Kickstart)</td><td>Fast</td><td>High</td><td>Many identical servers</td></tr><tr><td>Imaging / cloning</td><td>Fast</td><td>Very high</td><td>Standardized fleets</td></tr><tr><td>VM template / cloud image</td><td>Fastest</td><td>Very high</td><td>Self-service, on-prem & cloud</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Migrations reuse these mechanics: <span class='keyterm'>P2V</span> (physical-to-virtual) lifts a bare-metal server into a VM, <span class='keyterm'>V2P</span> reverses it, and <span class='keyterm'>V2V</span> moves a VM between hypervisor platforms. P2V is extremely common as organizations consolidate physical servers into virtualized and cloud environments.</p><h3>Bare-Metal vs Virtualized Targets</h3><p>Any of these methods can install to a <span class='keyterm'>bare-metal</span> target — the OS installed directly on the physical server with resources not shared among installations — or to a <span class='keyterm'>virtualized</span> target where the OS is installed inside a hypervisor-managed VM. Bare metal is the traditional choice and provides the isolation, reliability, and performance that some regulated industries require, but it can cost more and uses hardware less efficiently. Virtualized installs share physical resources among many VMs, deliver fault tolerance and scalability, and use hardware far more efficiently, though they may not satisfy every security requirement. The same graphical or command-line installer runs against either target.</p><h3>Pre-Installation Checks and Interface Choice</h3><p>Before any install you must confirm the hardware meets the OS requirements — and distinguish <strong>minimum</strong> from <strong>recommended</strong> specifications, since the minimum often yields an unusably slow server. Verify the components appear on the OS vendor's <span class='keyterm'>Hardware Compatibility List (HCL)</span> so device drivers exist for every component; an unsupported NIC or storage controller can derail an otherwise clean install. A further choice made during installation is whether to deploy a <strong>GUI</strong> or a <strong>command-line-only</strong> environment. A GUI is easier to navigate but consumes more resources; a CLI build (Linux without a desktop, or Windows <span class='keyterm'>Server Core</span>, available since Server 2008) has a smaller footprint, better performance, and a reduced attack surface. For a low-maintenance static web server, a CLI-only VM with minimal resources is the efficient call; for a server that many staff will log into to install and remove software, a GUI is justified.</p><h3>Remote Administration After Install</h3><p>Most servers should be administered remotely regardless of which interface is installed locally. Even a Server Core box can be configured from a remote GUI workstation, letting the server itself run the lean command-line environment. Common remote-access options are <span class='keyterm'>SSH</span> (secured command-line access, typically to Linux), <span class='keyterm'>RDP (Remote Desktop Protocol)</span> (secured graphical access, typically to Windows, port 3389), and <span class='keyterm'>VNC</span> (graphical access used on both Linux and Windows). This means the installation interface choice need not dictate the day-to-day management experience.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>You must stand up forty identical RHEL web servers for a new app tier this weekend. You build one golden source, capture an image, and PXE-boot the rest, each referencing a <strong>Kickstart</strong> answer file that also slipstreams the latest patches — turning a multi-day manual effort into an unattended overnight run.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div>Match the scenario to the method: 'deploy 200 identical web servers overnight' points to imaging or unattended/PXE, never to attended DVD installs. Remember Kickstart = Linux answer file, slipstream = Windows automated install with patches/drivers baked in, and always confirm hardware is on the <strong>HCL</strong> before you begin.</div>"}
);
SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Partitioning — MBR vs GPT", body:"<p>Before a file system can be created, the disk must be divided into <span class='keyterm'>partitions</span>, and the layout of those partitions is recorded in a <span class='keyterm'>partition table</span> at the start of the disk. SK0-005 expects you to compare the two partition-table schemes — the older <span class='keyterm'>Master Boot Record (MBR)</span> and the newer <span class='keyterm'>GUID Partition Table (GPT)</span> — and to know their hard limits, because those limits drive real design decisions on modern servers.</p><h3>Master Boot Record (MBR)</h3><p>MBR dates to the early 1980s and stores its partition table in the very first 512-byte sector of the disk. Its two defining constraints are well known on the exam: it supports a maximum of <strong>four partitions</strong> and cannot address disks larger than <strong>2 TB</strong>. To work around the four-partition cap, MBR allows up to three <span class='keyterm'>primary partitions</span> plus one <span class='keyterm'>extended partition</span>. The system boots from a primary partition; the extended partition is itself subdivided into <span class='keyterm'>logical partitions</span>, which lets you exceed four usable volumes even though the table records only four entries. MBR pairs with legacy <span class='keyterm'>BIOS</span> firmware.</p><h3>GUID Partition Table (GPT)</h3><p>GPT is part of the <span class='keyterm'>UEFI</span> specification and removes MBR's ceilings. It supports a far larger number of partitions (commonly 128 by default) and recognizes drives <strong>well beyond 2 TB</strong>. GPT also stores a backup copy of the partition table at the end of the disk and uses CRC checksums to detect corruption, making it more resilient. The trade-off is that GPT requires server firmware that supports <strong>UEFI</strong>; pure-BIOS systems cannot boot from a GPT disk.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Attribute</th><th>MBR</th><th>GPT</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Maximum partitions</td><td>4 (3 primary + 1 extended)</td><td>Large (128+ typical)</td></tr><tr><td>Maximum disk size</td><td>2 TB</td><td>Far greater than 2 TB</td></tr><tr><td>Firmware</td><td>BIOS</td><td>UEFI required</td></tr><tr><td>Table redundancy</td><td>Single copy, no checksum</td><td>Primary + backup, CRC protected</td></tr><tr><td>Partition types</td><td>Primary, extended, logical</td><td>Uniform GPT partitions</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Choosing a Scheme and Partition Types</h3><p>The decision rule is simple: choose <strong>GPT if the drive is 2 TB or larger, or if more than four partitions are required</strong> — and since modern servers usually exceed both thresholds, GPT is the default recommendation. MBR remains acceptable on older hardware with smaller drives and modest partition needs. Both Windows and Linux can read and write either table format, and both MBR and GPT can be combined with Windows Basic or Dynamic disk configurations.</p><p>Within a partition you still distinguish roles. On a booting MBR disk, the boot loader lives on a primary partition. On Linux it is common to carve dedicated partitions for the file-system root (<code>/</code>), <code>/home</code>, <code>/var/log</code>, and a <span class='keyterm'>swap</span> partition for virtual memory. On Windows a typical layout reserves <strong>C:</strong> for the OS, applications, page file, and updates, with a separate <strong>D:</strong> (ideally a second physical disk) for data so that OS and data I/O do not compete on the same spindle. Separating roles onto different partitions improves manageability, isolates log growth from the OS, and simplifies backup and recovery.</p><h3>Windows Basic and Dynamic Disks</h3><p>After the OS is installed, Windows offers two ways to organize storage. By default it uses <span class='keyterm'>Basic Disks</span>, where divisions are called <strong>partitions</strong>. The more flexible option is <span class='keyterm'>Dynamic Disks</span>, where divisions are called <strong>volumes</strong> and where Windows can manage simple, spanned, striped (RAID 0), mirrored (RAID 1), and striped-with-parity (RAID 5) configurations in software. Simple and spanned volumes can be expanded to add capacity, and mirrored or RAID 5 volumes can be repaired after a drive failure. Importantly, both MBR and GPT partition tables work with either Basic or Dynamic disk configurations — the table format and the disk-management model are independent choices. A common Windows file-server build configures three drives as Dynamic Disks in a software RAID 5 array to gain both speed and fault tolerance.</p><h3>Linux LVM</h3><p>Linux adds a powerful abstraction called <span class='keyterm'>LVM (Logical Volume Manager)</span> that is far more flexible than fixed partitions. LVM stacks three layers: <span class='keyterm'>physical volumes (PVs)</span> are the actual installed disks (they need not be identical in size); <span class='keyterm'>volume groups (VGs)</span> aggregate the capacity of one or more PVs into a single pool; and <span class='keyterm'>logical volumes (LVs)</span> are carved from a VG and then formatted with ext4 or XFS for use. LVM's headline benefit is online growth — to add space, an admin installs a new disk as a PV, adds it to the VG, and extends the LV, all without repartitioning or rebooting and with only a brief unmount. This makes capacity expansion nearly seamless compared with the destructive repartitioning that rigid schemes require.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>You provision a server with a 6 TB array and need six volumes. MBR is disqualified twice over — it cannot address past 2 TB and cannot record six partitions. You select GPT and confirm the firmware is set to UEFI before installing.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div>Memorize the two MBR ceilings cold: <strong>4 partitions</strong> and <strong>2 TB</strong>. Any scenario that breaches either one is a GPT (and therefore UEFI) answer.</div>"}
);
SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"File Systems — NTFS, ReFS, ext4, XFS, ZFS, FAT32", body:"<p>A <span class='keyterm'>file system</span> manages how data is stored and retrieved on a partition or volume: data is broken into chunks, each labeled for organization and fast retrieval. File systems are largely OS-specific, though some cross-compatibility exists, and choosing the right one per server role is a 2.1 skill. Most modern server file systems are <span class='keyterm'>journaling</span> file systems — they record pending changes in a journal first so that, after a crash, the volume can be repaired quickly and consistently instead of requiring a full scan.</p><h3>Windows File Systems</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>NTFS (New Technology File System)</span> is the primary Windows server file system. It provides journaling, granular <strong>permissions</strong> (ACLs) for security, encryption via EFS, compression, quotas, and supports <span class='keyterm'>BitLocker</span> full-volume encryption. NTFS is the default choice for both OS (C:) and data (D:) volumes because of its security and stability. <span class='keyterm'>ReFS (Resilient File System)</span> is Microsoft's newer file system built for massive scale and integrity — it targets enormous capacities, offers automatic integrity checking and self-healing on mirrored Storage Spaces, and scales further than NTFS, though it lacks some NTFS features. <span class='keyterm'>FAT32</span> is an older, simple file system with no permissions and a 4 GB per-file limit; it survives mainly on removable media and for cross-OS compatibility, not on production servers.</p><h3>Linux File Systems</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>ext4</span> is the long-standing default for many Linux distributions — stable, mature, journaling, and reliable. <span class='keyterm'>XFS</span> is a high-performance journaling file system favored in enterprise Linux and is the <strong>default for RHEL</strong>; it excels at large files, large volumes, and parallel I/O. You format these from the command line:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Action</th><th>Command</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Format a volume ext4</td><td><code>mkfs.ext4 /dev/sdb1</code></td></tr><tr><td>Format a volume XFS</td><td><code>mkfs.xfs /dev/sdb1</code></td></tr></tbody></table><p><span class='keyterm'>ZFS</span>, created by Sun Microsystems (open-source as OpenZFS), combines the file system and volume manager into one. It is scalable and efficient, supporting very large volumes, ACL permissions, built-in compression, snapshots, and checksum-based data integrity. ZFS is popular on Unix and enterprise Linux where data integrity is paramount. Note that 'ZFS' is not actually an acronym.</p><h3>Virtualization File System</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>VMFS (Virtual Machine File System)</span> is VMware's clustered file system for ESXi. It is optimized to host multiple VM disk images: each image is writable only by its own VM, yet multiple hosts can access the file system simultaneously, enabling shared storage for clusters without locking the entire volume to a single host.</p><table><thead><tr><th>File System</th><th>Platform</th><th>Key Attributes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>NTFS</td><td>Windows</td><td>Journaling, permissions, BitLocker, stable default</td></tr><tr><td>ReFS</td><td>Windows</td><td>Massive scale, integrity/self-healing, resiliency</td></tr><tr><td>FAT32</td><td>Cross-OS / removable</td><td>Simple, no permissions, 4 GB file cap</td></tr><tr><td>ext4</td><td>Linux</td><td>Mature journaling default</td></tr><tr><td>XFS</td><td>Linux</td><td>High performance, large files, RHEL default</td></tr><tr><td>ZFS</td><td>Linux/Unix</td><td>Scalable, compression, snapshots, integrity</td></tr><tr><td>VMFS</td><td>ESXi</td><td>Multi-host VM disk hosting, clustered</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Why Journaling Matters</h3><p>The reason nearly every modern server file system journals is recovery speed and integrity. Without a journal, an abrupt power loss or crash mid-write can leave the file system's metadata inconsistent, forcing a slow full-volume consistency check and risking data loss. A journaling file system first records its intended changes in a dedicated journal; on restart it simply replays or discards the journal, returning to a consistent state in seconds. This is why NTFS, ReFS, ext4, XFS, and ZFS all journal, while legacy FAT32 does not — a key reason FAT32 is unsuitable for servers beyond removable media and compatibility roles. Beyond journaling, advanced file systems add <span class='keyterm'>extended attributes</span> (metadata such as ACL permissions and labels), large-file and large-volume support, and in the case of ReFS and ZFS, checksum-based integrity that can detect and even self-heal silent corruption.</p><h3>Matching File System to Server Role</h3><p>Selecting a file system is a per-role decision tied to the server's purpose. A Windows file server hosting confidential user data needs NTFS for its permissions, auditing, and BitLocker support. A Windows server demanding extreme capacity with automatic integrity checking — for example backing a large Storage Spaces pool — is a candidate for ReFS. On Linux, a general-purpose server is well served by the mature ext4, while an enterprise RHEL deployment defaults to XFS for its superior performance with large files and parallel I/O. When data integrity, snapshots, and built-in compression top the requirements list on a Unix or Linux box, ZFS is the standout. And whenever ESXi hosts must share access to the same VM disk images in a cluster, VMFS is the clustered file system that allows multiple hosts to read and write the volume while each VM disk stays writable only by its own VM.</p><h3>Storage Strategy Examples</h3><p>File system choice pairs with partition strategy. A Windows admin separates the OS and applications onto C: (NTFS) and user data onto D: (NTFS), ideally on different physical disks so I/O does not compete. A Linux web-server admin might create separate partitions for <code>/</code>, <code>swap</code>, and a large <code>/var</code> (formatted XFS) to hold web content and logs, omitting <code>/home</code> entirely because no users store data there. The file system rides on top of whatever partition or LVM volume you created — the two decisions, layout and format, work together to deliver the security, performance, and reliability the role demands.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>You deploy a RHEL database server with a 20 TB data volume requiring high throughput and crash resilience. You format it <strong>XFS</strong> (the RHEL default, strong with large files and parallel I/O) on a GPT/UEFI disk, reserving ext4 only for the small boot partition — a textbook match of file system to role.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div>Anchor the defaults: NTFS for Windows, XFS for RHEL, ext4 elsewhere on Linux. Pick ReFS when the scenario stresses huge capacity and integrity, ZFS when it stresses snapshots/compression/data-integrity on Linux, and VMFS when ESXi hosts share VM storage. FAT32's 4 GB file cap and lack of permissions rule it out for servers.</div>"}
);
SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"IP Addressing & Subnetting for Servers", body:"<p>Objective <strong>2.2</strong> requires you to configure servers to use network infrastructure services, and that begins with logical addressing. Every node on a TCP/IP network has up to three identities: a <span class='keyterm'>MAC address</span> (physical, layer 2, burned into the NIC), an <span class='keyterm'>IP address</span> (logical, layer 3, assigned by the admin or DHCP), and a <span class='keyterm'>hostname</span> (human-friendly). The MAC is preset by the vendor and the hostname is chosen at install; the value you most often configure is the IP address and its companions: subnet mask, default gateway, and DNS server(s).</p><h3>IPv4 Fundamentals</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>IPv4</span> addresses are <strong>32 bits</strong>, written as four 8-bit octets, yielding roughly <strong>4.3 billion</strong> addresses — a pool that is now exhausted. Addresses split into a <span class='keyterm'>network ID</span> and a <span class='keyterm'>host ID</span>, and the <span class='keyterm'>subnet mask</span> defines the boundary. For example, 192.168.2.200 with mask 255.255.255.0 (/24) has network ID 192.168.2.0 and host ID .200. Masks are written in decimal or CIDR bit-count notation.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Class</th><th>Default mask</th><th>CIDR</th><th>First octet</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>A</td><td>255.0.0.0</td><td>/8</td><td>1&ndash;126</td></tr><tr><td>B</td><td>255.255.0.0</td><td>/16</td><td>128&ndash;191</td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>255.255.255.0</td><td>/24</td><td>192&ndash;223</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Three ranges are reserved by <span class='keyterm'>RFC 1918</span> for private internal use and are not routable on the public Internet: <strong>10.0.0.0&ndash;10.255.255.255</strong>, <strong>172.16.0.0&ndash;172.31.255.255</strong>, and <strong>192.168.0.0&ndash;192.168.255.255</strong>. To reach the Internet from these ranges, a router or hypervisor performs <span class='keyterm'>NAT (Network Address Translation)</span>, substituting the organization's public IP for internal private addresses. Two special addresses round this out: the loopback <strong>127.0.0.1</strong> (the host refers to itself, used for troubleshooting) and the <span class='keyterm'>APIPA</span> range <strong>169.254.0.0/16</strong>, which a client self-assigns when it cannot reach a DHCP server — a telltale sign that DHCP leasing failed.</p><h3>IPv6</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>IPv6</span> uses <strong>128-bit</strong> addresses (~3.4 x 10^38 of them), written in hexadecimal, and improves routing and built-in encryption. Key ranges: <code>::1/128</code> is loopback (like 127.0.0.1), <code>FE80::/10</code> is link-local (like APIPA), and <code>2000::/3</code> is global unicast (Internet-routable, like public IPv4). Public services have largely moved to IPv6 while many internal networks remain on IPv4.</p><h3>Static vs Dynamic on Servers</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>static</span> configuration is entered manually — IP, mask, gateway, DNS — and never changes unless you change it. A <span class='keyterm'>dynamic</span> configuration is leased from a DHCP server. The exam rule: <strong>servers and infrastructure devices (routers, managed switches, security appliances) use static addresses</strong> so clients can reliably find them, while ordinary clients use DHCP. A static address must be unique and error-free, so admins track assignments in a spreadsheet or IPAM tool.</p><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>Static</th><th>Dynamic (DHCP)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>How set</td><td>Manually by admin</td><td>Leased automatically</td></tr><tr><td>Stability</td><td>Unchanging</td><td>May renew/change</td></tr><tr><td>Best for</td><td>Servers, gateways, printers</td><td>Workstations, mobile clients</td></tr><tr><td>Risk</td><td>Typos, duplicate IPs</td><td>Scope exhaustion, APIPA on failure</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The Three Node Identities</h3><p>Every node carries up to three identities you must keep straight. The <span class='keyterm'>MAC address</span> is a physical, layer-2 identifier hardcoded into the NIC (e.g. 00:0a:97:9e:86:16); its first half identifies the vendor and the second half the device, and switches reference it. The <span class='keyterm'>IP address</span> is a logical, layer-3 identifier assigned by the admin or DHCP; routers reference it to direct traffic between networks. The <span class='keyterm'>hostname</span> is a human-friendly name the protocols ignore but that people use. On a server you typically configure only the IP details, since the MAC is vendor-set and the hostname is chosen at install.</p><h3>Network ID, Host ID, and the Mask in Depth</h3><p>The split between network and host portions follows the class defaults — Class A uses the first octet for the network (mask /8), Class B the first two (/16), and Class C the first three (/24) — but those defaults are adjustable via the subnet mask to suit the administrator's design. For 192.168.2.200 /24, the network ID is 192.168.2.0 and everything in the last octet is host space, giving 254 usable hosts. Administrators often borrow host bits to create more, smaller subnets, trading hosts-per-network for number-of-networks. Because IPv4 exhaustion is real, organizations track every assignment with <span class='keyterm'>IP address management (IPAM)</span> software as branches open and close and mobile devices come and go; some firms even broker IPv4 address blocks commercially.</p><h3>NAT and Default Gateway</h3><p>Private RFC 1918 addresses cannot route on the Internet, so a <span class='keyterm'>NAT</span> device — a router or hypervisor service — substitutes the organization's single public IP for outbound traffic from internal hosts, hiding the internal scheme behind one public identity. To reach any remote network at all, each host needs a <span class='keyterm'>default gateway</span>: the IP of the router interface on the host's local segment, the 'door out' of the subnet. Clients in 192.168.1.0/24 use 192.168.1.1; clients in 192.168.2.0/24 use 192.168.2.1. Misconfigure the gateway and a host can reach its own subnet but nothing beyond it — a classic troubleshooting signature.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A new server can ping other hosts on 192.168.2.0/24 but cannot reach the Internet or other subnets. Its IP and mask are correct, but the <strong>default gateway</strong> field is blank. Adding 192.168.2.1 restores routed connectivity — the host simply had no door out of its local segment.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div>Seeing a <strong>169.254.x.x</strong> address means the client failed to lease from DHCP — start troubleshooting there. Memorize the three RFC 1918 ranges, loopback 127.0.0.1, and the IPv6 equivalents (::1 loopback, FE80::/10 link-local, 2000::/3 global unicast). Production servers get <strong>static</strong> IPs, usually inside an isolated subnet.</div>"}
);
SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"DNS Configuration & Records", body:"<p>Humans use names; computers use numbers. <span class='keyterm'>Name resolution</span> bridges the gap, and the dominant mechanism on both the Internet and internal networks is the <span class='keyterm'>Domain Name System (DNS)</span>. A node's <span class='keyterm'>hostname</span> gains context from a domain name to form a <span class='keyterm'>Fully Qualified Domain Name (FQDN)</span>: a host <code>computer1</code> on the <code>mycompany.internal</code> network has the FQDN <code>computer1.mycompany.internal</code>. DNS listens on <strong>port 53</strong> (both TCP and UDP) and is one of the most critical services on any network — when DNS fails, name-based access fails everywhere.</p><h3>How DNS Replaces the Hosts File</h3><p>The most primitive name resolution is the local <span class='keyterm'>hosts file</span> (<code>C:\\Windows\\System32\\drivers\\etc\\hosts</code> on Windows, <code>/etc/hosts</code> on Linux). An entry looks like <code>192.168.1.42 dev-server</code>, and lines beginning with <code>#</code> are comments. Hosts files are static: change one IP or name and every machine's file must be edited, which does not scale. They remain handy only for isolated, unregistered hosts (for example a developer's private test server). DNS replaces this with a dynamic, replicated database. On an internal network, one or more DNS servers host a zone named for the company (e.g. <code>mycompany.internal</code>) containing a record for every node — 1,000 nodes means at least 1,000 records. Most networks run at least two DNS servers as replicas for fault tolerance.</p><h3>Common Resource Records</h3><p>DNS stores typed <span class='keyterm'>resource records</span>. You must recognize the core types and what each maps:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Record</th><th>Maps</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>A</strong></td><td>Name &rarr; IPv4</td><td>Forward lookup to a 32-bit address</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AAAA</strong></td><td>Name &rarr; IPv6</td><td>Forward lookup to a 128-bit address</td></tr><tr><td><strong>CNAME</strong></td><td>Alias &rarr; canonical name</td><td>Point one name at another name</td></tr><tr><td><strong>MX</strong></td><td>Domain &rarr; mail server</td><td>Route email; uses a priority value</td></tr><tr><td><strong>PTR</strong></td><td>IP &rarr; name</td><td>Reverse lookup</td></tr><tr><td><strong>NS</strong></td><td>Zone &rarr; authoritative server</td><td>Delegates which server answers</td></tr><tr><td><strong>SOA</strong></td><td>Zone metadata</td><td>Start of authority, serial, timers</td></tr><tr><td><strong>TXT</strong></td><td>Name &rarr; text</td><td>SPF/DKIM, verification strings</td></tr><tr><td><strong>SRV</strong></td><td>Service &rarr; host/port</td><td>Locate services (e.g. AD domain controllers)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Forward vs Reverse Lookup Zones</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>forward lookup zone</span> resolves a name to an IP and is queried by <strong>A</strong> and <strong>AAAA</strong> records — this is the everyday direction (you type a hostname, DNS returns an address). A <span class='keyterm'>reverse lookup zone</span> resolves an IP back to a name using <strong>PTR</strong> records and the special <code>in-addr.arpa</code> hierarchy. Reverse lookups matter for logging, troubleshooting, and especially mail servers, many of which reject messages from IPs lacking a valid PTR record (this is how anti-spam reverse-DNS checks work). A <strong>CNAME</strong> aliases one hostname to another (for example pointing <code>www</code> at <code>webserver03</code>) so you can move services without retraining users, while <strong>MX</strong> records direct a domain's email to the correct mail host, with lower priority numbers preferred.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>Outbound mail from your server is being rejected as spam. You confirm the A record resolves correctly but discover the public IP has no <strong>PTR</strong> record. Adding the reverse-lookup PTR entry restores deliverability — receiving servers could not verify the sender.</div><h3>How a DNS Query Resolves</h3><p>When an internal host wants to reach another by name, it sends a query to its configured DNS server. If that server holds the record in its zone, it answers authoritatively; if not, it can resolve the name recursively up the Internet hierarchy and cache the result so subsequent lookups are instant. This is why DNS configuration on every server must include at least one — preferably two — DNS server addresses; without name resolution, almost nothing name-based works, from logging into Active Directory to sending email. The exam treats DNS as one of the most critical services on the network precisely because so many other services depend on it.</p><h3>Why Port 53 Uses Both TCP and UDP</h3><p>DNS listens on port 53 over <strong>both</strong> UDP and TCP, and the distinction is worth understanding. Ordinary name queries are small and use <span class='keyterm'>UDP</span> for speed and low overhead. When a response is too large for a single UDP datagram, or when a <span class='keyterm'>zone transfer</span> replicates the full zone database between DNS servers, DNS falls back to <span class='keyterm'>TCP</span> for reliable delivery. That is why firewall rules for DNS frequently permit 53 on both protocols, and why a firewall blocking TCP 53 can break replication while normal lookups still appear to work.</p><h3>Redundancy and Zone Replication</h3><p>Most networks run at least two DNS servers configured as replicas so the loss of one does not take name resolution down. The authoritative server for a zone is identified by its <strong>NS</strong> records, and the zone's <strong>SOA</strong> record holds metadata including a serial number and refresh timers that control how often secondaries pull updates. When you add, change, or remove a host, the corresponding A/AAAA (and ideally PTR) records must be updated, and the change propagates to the replicas. In an Active Directory environment, DNS is frequently co-located on domain controllers and integrated into AD so replication rides on AD's own multi-master replication, improving both resilience and consistency. <strong>SRV</strong> records are how clients locate AD domain controllers and other services by querying for a service rather than a fixed host.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div>Lock in the mappings: A = IPv4, AAAA = IPv6, CNAME = alias, MX = mail (priority), PTR = reverse (IP-to-name), NS = authoritative server, SOA = zone metadata, SRV = service location, TXT = SPF/DKIM. DNS = port 53 on <strong>both UDP (queries) and TCP (large responses/zone transfers)</strong>. Forward zones use A/AAAA; reverse zones use PTR.</div>"}
);
SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"DHCP Scopes & Reservations", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP)</span> automates IP configuration so administrators do not hand-assign every client. The admin installs the DHCP service, defines a <span class='keyterm'>scope</span> (a pool of addresses plus mask), adds options (default gateway, DNS servers, and more), and starts the service. Clients then lease a configuration at boot. DHCP is a lightweight service that uses <strong>UDP port 67</strong> (server) and <strong>port 68</strong> (client).</p><h3>The DORA Lease Process</h3><p>Lease acquisition follows four broadcast steps, memorized as <span class='keyterm'>DORA</span>:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>Message</th><th>Sender</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>D</td><td>DHCP<strong>Discover</strong></td><td>Client</td><td>'Is there a DHCP server?'</td></tr><tr><td>O</td><td>DHCP<strong>Offer</strong></td><td>Server</td><td>'Here is an available address'</td></tr><tr><td>R</td><td>DHCP<strong>Request</strong></td><td>Client</td><td>'I would like that address'</td></tr><tr><td>A</td><td>DHCP<strong>Acknowledge</strong></td><td>Server</td><td>'It is leased to you'</td></tr></tbody></table><p>The client then configures its NIC with the supplied IP, mask, gateway, and DNS. If <em>no</em> server answers, the client self-assigns an <span class='keyterm'>APIPA</span> address from <strong>169.254.0.0/16</strong> and has no real connectivity — a clear signal the DORA process failed.</p><h3>Leases and Renewal</h3><p>A lease is time-limited, not permanent. Clients periodically <strong>renew</strong> (typically attempting renewal at 50% of the lease duration) to tell the server the address is still in use so it is not handed to another client. A workstation may hold the same address for weeks, but because it is only leased, servers — which need a fixed identity — should not rely on it. That is why servers use static addresses or DHCP <strong>reservations</strong>.</p><h3>Reservations and Options</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>reservation</span> ties a specific IP address to a specific client's <strong>MAC address</strong> within the scope. The device still uses DHCP (so configuration stays centralized), but it always receives the same IP — ideal for printers, infrastructure, and servers that benefit from centralized management yet need consistent addressing. <span class='keyterm'>DHCP options</span> are additional settings delivered alongside the address; common ones include option 3 (default gateway/router), option 6 (DNS servers), option 15 (DNS domain name), and option 42 (NTP servers). Options can be set scope-wide or server-wide.</p><h3>DHCP Relay</h3><p>DHCP relies on broadcasts, and routers do not forward broadcasts between subnets. So a single DHCP server cannot directly hear Discover messages from clients on other segments. A <span class='keyterm'>DHCP relay agent</span> (an <span class='keyterm'>IP helper</span> configured on the router or a dedicated host) listens for client broadcasts on a remote subnet and forwards them as unicast to the central DHCP server, then relays the responses back. This lets one centralized DHCP server service many subnets, avoiding a server on every segment.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Concept</th><th>Role</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Scope</td><td>Pool of leasable addresses + mask</td></tr><tr><td>Lease</td><td>Time-limited grant, renewed at ~50%</td></tr><tr><td>Reservation</td><td>MAC-locked fixed address inside a scope</td></tr><tr><td>Option</td><td>Extra settings (gateway, DNS, NTP)</td></tr><tr><td>Relay / IP helper</td><td>Forwards broadcasts across subnets</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Standing Up a DHCP Server</h3><p>Configuring DHCP follows a clear sequence: install the DHCP service; define a <strong>scope</strong> with a range of addresses and the matching subnet mask; configure scope <strong>options</strong> such as the default gateway and one or more DNS servers; and start the service so clients can lease. Within a scope you usually define <span class='keyterm'>exclusions</span> — addresses inside the range that DHCP must never hand out because they are statically assigned to servers, routers, or printers. Forgetting exclusions invites an <span class='keyterm'>address conflict</span>, where DHCP leases an address already in static use, breaking connectivity for both devices. Good practice is to carve the subnet so a block of low or high addresses is reserved for static infrastructure and the DHCP scope covers the remainder.</p><h3>The Lease Lifecycle in Detail</h3><p>After DORA completes, the lease has a finite duration. The client attempts <strong>renewal</strong> at roughly 50% of the lease time by unicasting a Request directly to the leasing server; if that server is unreachable, it tries again at about 87.5% (the rebinding phase) by broadcasting to any DHCP server. Only if all attempts fail does the lease expire and the client fall back to APIPA. This staged renewal keeps addresses stable for long periods while still reclaiming them when devices leave. Lease duration is a tuning decision: short leases suit highly mobile environments (guest Wi-Fi) so addresses recycle quickly, while long leases reduce traffic on stable networks. Because servers need permanence, they either sit outside the scope on static addresses or use <strong>reservations</strong>.</p><h3>Reservations vs Static in Practice</h3><p>A reservation and a static address both yield a fixed IP, but a reservation keeps the device under centralized DHCP management — you change its gateway or DNS once on the server and it propagates, rather than visiting the device. This makes reservations attractive for printers and appliances that benefit from consistent addressing yet should be managed centrally. True static addressing, entered on the device itself, remains the convention for critical servers and network gear that must come up correctly even if DHCP is down.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>Workstations on the second-floor VLAN suddenly cannot obtain addresses while the first floor is fine. The DHCP server sits on the first-floor subnet, and the second-floor router lost its <strong>IP helper</strong> configuration after a reset — so client broadcasts never reach the server. Restoring the relay address fixes the entire floor at once.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div>Know <strong>DORA</strong> in order and that it is all broadcast. Clients renew at ~50% of lease time. When clients on a remote subnet cannot get addresses but the local subnet can, suspect a missing <strong>DHCP relay / IP helper</strong>. Use <strong>exclusions</strong> to protect static addresses, and a <strong>reservation</strong> to give a device a permanent address while keeping it under DHCP management.</div>"}
);
SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"VLANs & Network Segmentation", body:"<p>Network administrators divide networks into <span class='keyterm'>segments</span> for security and performance. Each segment carries a distinct network ID, and traffic between segments must pass through a <span class='keyterm'>router</span>, whose interface in each segment serves as that segment's <span class='keyterm'>default gateway</span>. By tradition the gateway takes the first or last address in the range (e.g. 192.168.1.1). Routing between segments is also a control point: the router can permit web traffic between development and production while blocking file-sharing, for example.</p><h3>Subnets vs VLANs</h3><p>There are two ways to segment. <span class='keyterm'>Subnets</span> are divisions based on <strong>routers</strong> and IP network IDs; hosts in a subnet typically connect to the same switches near the same router interface, which limits how physically dispersed they can be. <span class='keyterm'>VLANs (Virtual LANs)</span> are divisions based on <strong>switches</strong> and operate per-port. Each switch port is assigned to a VLAN, and a port can only communicate with other ports in the same VLAN. Crucially, a VLAN can <strong>span multiple switches</strong>, so hosts on one logical segment can sit anywhere physically. This decouples logical grouping from physical location.</p><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>Subnet</th><th>VLAN</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Based on</td><td>Router / IP network ID</td><td>Switch / port assignment</td></tr><tr><td>Layer</td><td>Layer 3</td><td>Layer 2</td></tr><tr><td>Physical constraint</td><td>Hosts near same gateway</td><td>Can span switches/locations</td></tr><tr><td>Inter-segment routing</td><td>Router</td><td>Router or layer-3 switch</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>802.1Q Tagging and Trunking</h3><p>When VLAN traffic must cross the link between two switches, the switch needs to know which VLAN each frame belongs to. The <span class='keyterm'>IEEE 802.1Q</span> standard inserts a small <strong>VLAN tag</strong> into the Ethernet frame header carrying the VLAN ID. A link that carries multiple tagged VLANs between switches (or to a router/hypervisor) is a <span class='keyterm'>trunk port</span>. By contrast, an <span class='keyterm'>access port</span> belongs to a single VLAN and connects end devices, which send and receive <em>untagged</em> frames — the switch applies and strips the tag. A special <span class='keyterm'>native VLAN</span> on a trunk carries untagged traffic. VMs participate too: a <span class='keyterm'>vNIC</span> attaches to a virtual switch and can join a VLAN just like a physical host, each vNIC having its own MAC and IP.</p><h3>NIC Teaming</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>NIC teaming</span> (also called link aggregation or bonding) combines two or more physical NICs into one logical interface. It serves two goals: <strong>increased bandwidth</strong> (the combined throughput exceeds any single NIC, useful for busy VM hosts) and <strong>fault tolerance</strong> (if one NIC or cable fails, traffic continues over the remaining members). Administrators often over-provision a host with multiple teamed NICs so total bandwidth comfortably exceeds anticipated demand. Teaming pairs naturally with trunking — a teamed, trunked uplink can carry many VLANs with redundancy.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>The Sales group is spread across three floors but must share one broadcast domain and security policy. Routing/subnetting alone would force them onto the same physical switch. Instead you assign their ports to <strong>VLAN 20</strong> across all three floor switches, carry VLAN 20 over <strong>802.1Q trunks</strong> between switches, and team the uplinks for redundancy.</div><h3>Why Segment at All</h3><p>Segmentation serves two intertwined goals: <strong>security</strong> and <strong>performance</strong>. Security-wise, isolating traffic limits the blast radius of a compromise — a workstation VLAN cannot directly reach a server-management VLAN unless routing explicitly permits it, and broadcast traffic is contained within each segment. Performance-wise, smaller broadcast domains mean less broadcast noise reaching every host, which matters as networks grow. A simple example separates a development environment (192.168.1.0/24) from production (192.168.2.0/24); with no router between them there is zero connectivity, and adding a router lets the admin permit only specific traffic — say web between the two but not file sharing. VLANs accomplish the same logical separation without forcing hosts onto the same physical switch.</p><h3>Inter-VLAN Routing</h3><p>VLANs separate traffic at layer 2, but hosts in different VLANs still need a layer-3 device to communicate when policy allows it. That device is a router or a <span class='keyterm'>layer-3 switch</span> performing <span class='keyterm'>inter-VLAN routing</span>, often via a single trunked 'router-on-a-stick' link carrying every VLAN's subinterface. Each VLAN maps to its own IP subnet and default gateway, so the concepts reinforce each other: one VLAN, one subnet, one gateway. This is why VLANs and subnets are usually designed together even though they operate at different layers.</p><h3>Virtual Networking and VLANs</h3><p>Virtualization extends VLANs into the host. A VM's <span class='keyterm'>vNIC</span> attaches to a <span class='keyterm'>virtual switch</span> and can be assigned a VLAN ID, so VMs participate in the same segmentation scheme as physical hosts. VMs typically have four network modes: <strong>none</strong> (no NIC), <strong>local</strong> (only other VMs on the host), <strong>host-only</strong> (only the host, not the physical network), and <strong>bridged</strong> (full physical-network/Internet access, used for production VMs like DNS or web servers). In Hyper-V these correspond to public, private, and internal virtual switch types. Teamed, trunked uplinks from the host carry many VLANs to the virtual switches with redundancy, knitting virtual and physical segmentation into one consistent design.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>Voice phones and PCs share the same cabling but must be isolated for QoS and security. You assign phones to VLAN 10 and PCs to VLAN 20 on the same access switches, carry both over <strong>802.1Q trunks</strong> to the core, and a layer-3 switch routes between them — voice and data stay logically separate without running new cable.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div>Remember the one-liner: <strong>subnets divide via routers, VLANs divide via switches</strong>. 802.1Q = the tagging standard; a <strong>trunk</strong> carries multiple tagged VLANs while an <strong>access</strong> port carries one untagged VLAN. Inter-VLAN traffic needs a router or layer-3 switch. NIC teaming = bandwidth + redundancy.</div>"}
);
SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Server Roles & Services", body:"<p>Objective <strong>2.3</strong> covers configuring and maintaining server functions and features. Standing up a server starts by defining its <span class='keyterm'>role</span>, because the role dictates which of the four major subsystems — <strong>CPU, memory, storage, network</strong> — must be emphasized. A single box can host multiple roles (DNS and DHCP are frequently co-located), but performance-sensitive roles like databases are best isolated.</p><h3>General-Purpose Servers</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>File servers</span> centralize business data for easier securing and backup; they need <strong>large, redundant, fast storage</strong> and fast networking. <span class='keyterm'>Print servers</span> queue and manage print jobs for shared devices, needing adequate storage, speed, and networking. <span class='keyterm'>Web servers</span> host websites and prioritize redundant, efficient <strong>network</strong> connectivity; basic static sites are small and easy to host.</p><h3>Application Servers</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Database servers</span> store data files and process queries; they demand large, fast, redundant <strong>storage</strong>, high availability, and ample <strong>CPU</strong> for queries — and you generally do <em>not</em> co-locate other services on them. <span class='keyterm'>Application/middleware servers</span> bridge databases to web or client front-ends, with requirements varying by use. <span class='keyterm'>Messaging/email servers</span> handle internal and Internet mail, needing redundant networking and storage. <span class='keyterm'>VPN servers</span> grant secured remote access and need redundant networking (often a dedicated appliance). <span class='keyterm'>Collaboration servers</span> host project sites with document management and versioning. <span class='keyterm'>VM hosts</span> exist solely to run VMs and must be strong across <em>all four</em> subsystems.</p><h3>Network Infrastructure Roles</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>DNS</span> provides name resolution and is among the most critical network services — it needs reliable, redundant networking and is frequently co-located with Active Directory domain controllers. <span class='keyterm'>DHCP</span> is lightweight, needing little hardware. These two services keep the rest of the network reachable and addressable.</p><h3>Directory Services and Domain Controllers</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>directory service</span> such as Microsoft <span class='keyterm'>Active Directory (AD)</span> centralizes user and computer accounts and authenticates identities. A server running this role is a <span class='keyterm'>domain controller (DC)</span>. When a user logs in, the DC verifies name and password and applies configurations. AD also delivers configuration via <span class='keyterm'>Group Policy</span>, so a Sales workstation can be configured differently from a Marketing one (deployed apps, security settings, mapped printers). Directory services require redundancy and efficient networking, since an unreachable DC blocks logins.</p><p>The directory stores both <span class='keyterm'>user account storage</span> — organizing accounts and verifying user passwords at logon — and <span class='keyterm'>computer account storage</span>, which proves the identity of client, mobile, and server devices by checking computer-account passwords much as it checks user passwords. Administrators organize these accounts in the AD Users and Computers console partly so Group Policy can target them by department and machine. Because so many services accept AD authentication, the directory underpins <span class='keyterm'>single sign-on (SSO)</span>: a user authenticates once and is then admitted to file, print, email, and database resources that all trust the same source. This makes the DC one of the most security-critical and availability-critical roles on the network, which is why DNS is so often co-located with it — AD depends on DNS (and SRV records) to let clients find domain controllers in the first place.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Role</th><th>Heaviest subsystem(s)</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>File</td><td>Storage + Network</td><td>Redundant, fast, large capacity</td></tr><tr><td>Print</td><td>Storage + Network</td><td>Spools jobs; cost-effective sharing</td></tr><tr><td>Web</td><td>Network</td><td>Redundant connectivity</td></tr><tr><td>Database</td><td>Storage + CPU</td><td>Do not co-locate other services</td></tr><tr><td>Directory (DC) / DNS</td><td>Network + redundancy</td><td>Critical; often co-located</td></tr><tr><td>DHCP</td><td>Lightweight</td><td>Minimal hardware</td></tr><tr><td>VM host</td><td>All four</td><td>Hosts any of the above as VMs</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Co-Location and Storage Management</h3><p>A single server can host multiple roles, and DNS with DHCP is the canonical pairing because both are network-infrastructure services and DHCP is so lightweight. The opposite rule applies to databases: a database server should generally <em>not</em> share its box, because its heavy storage and CPU demands would starve co-tenants and vice versa. For storage-heavy roles like file servers, performance hinges on fast disks, dedicated hardware RAID controllers, and efficient network connectivity, since clients reach shared folders over the network. Administrators use <span class='keyterm'>quotas</span> to cap per-user consumption, <span class='keyterm'>compression</span> to stretch capacity, and <span class='keyterm'>data deduplication</span> to eliminate redundant copies — all of which keep a file server healthy as data grows.</p><h3>Virtual Memory Considerations</h3><p>Every server role also depends on adequate RAM, and when physical RAM is exhausted the OS borrows disk space as <span class='keyterm'>virtual memory</span> — Windows calls this <span class='keyterm'>paging</span> (the <code>pagefile.sys</code>), Linux calls it <span class='keyterm'>swapping</span> (a swap partition or file). Data moves between RAM and disk in chunks called <strong>pages</strong>. Relying on virtual memory is a warning sign: disk is far slower than RAM, so heavy paging means the server lacks sufficient memory for its workload, and the real fix is more RAM or less load. Windows sizes the pagefile to at least the amount of RAM so it can capture a crash dump, and generally manages it automatically; Linux swap recommendations scale with RAM. Sizing virtual memory is part of right-sizing a role's hardware alongside the four subsystems.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>Users complain a busy SQL database server is sluggish. Monitoring shows constant paging because the box is also running a print service and the web role that someone co-located on it. You migrate those services off and add RAM, restoring the database to its baseline — a reminder that databases want isolation.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div>Map roles to subsystems: <strong>file = storage/network</strong>, <strong>database = storage/CPU (isolated, do not co-locate)</strong>, <strong>web/DNS = network + redundancy</strong>, <strong>VM host = all four</strong>. DNS+DHCP commonly co-locate. A domain controller runs the directory service (AD) that authenticates users and pushes Group Policy. Heavy <strong>paging/swapping</strong> signals insufficient RAM.</div>"}
);
SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Monitoring & Performance Metrics", body:"<p>Maintaining server functions (2.3) requires watching the same four subsystems — <strong>CPU, memory, storage, network</strong> — over time. The foundation is a <span class='keyterm'>baseline</span>: a documented snapshot of performance when the server is first brought online. Continuous monitoring against that baseline reveals how load changes as demand grows, separates normal from abnormal, and gives troubleshooting a known-good reference. Use consistent counters so comparisons are meaningful.</p><h3>Windows Monitoring</h3><p>Windows includes layered tools. <span class='keyterm'>Task Manager</span> gives real-time CPU, memory, and network views plus system <strong>uptime</strong>. <span class='keyterm'>Resource Monitor</span> breaks activity into the four subsystems. <span class='keyterm'>Reliability Monitor</span> charts historical crashes, installs, and changes. The primary tools are <span class='keyterm'>Performance Monitor</span> (real-time and recorded historical counters) and <span class='keyterm'>Event Viewer</span> (Application, Security, and System logs). It is easy to track too much, so start with a focused counter set:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Subsystem</th><th>Counter</th><th>Guidance</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>CPU</td><td>Processor &mdash; % Processor Time</td><td>Stay below <strong>80%</strong></td></tr><tr><td>CPU</td><td>Processor &mdash; % User Time</td><td>Split of user vs system load</td></tr><tr><td>Memory</td><td>Memory &mdash; Pages/sec</td><td>High = excessive paging</td></tr><tr><td>Network</td><td>Network Interface &mdash; Transfers/sec</td><td>Throughput trend</td></tr><tr><td>Disk</td><td>Physical Disk &mdash; Transfers/sec (IOPS)</td><td>Storage throughput</td></tr><tr><td>Disk</td><td>Physical Disk &mdash; Avg. Disk Queue Length</td><td>Backlog of pending I/O</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Disk performance is measured in <span class='keyterm'>IOPS (Input/Output Operations Per Second)</span> via counters like disk reads/sec, writes/sec, transfers/sec, and current queue length. If IOPS targets are missed, services such as SQL Server log errors and users feel slowness. Microsoft's CPU guideline is that <strong>% Processor Time should not exceed 80%</strong>.</p><h3>Alerts and Thresholds</h3><p>Monitoring earns its keep through <span class='keyterm'>alerts</span> tied to <span class='keyterm'>thresholds</span>. Performance Monitor can notify admins when a counter crosses a limit — for example, alerting when a file server's disk exceeds <strong>80% capacity</strong>, giving time to act before a full-disk outage.</p><h3>Linux Monitoring</h3><p>From the bash shell, several utilities cover the same ground:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Shows</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>top</code></td><td>Live processes by CPU (P) or memory (M); refreshes continuously</td></tr><tr><td><code>sar [interval] [count]</code></td><td>System activity; <code>-u</code> CPU, <code>-r</code> memory, <code>-b</code> disk I/O, <code>-n</code> network, <code>-S</code> swap</td></tr><tr><td><code>uptime</code></td><td>Time up, user count, load averages (1/5/15 min)</td></tr><tr><td><code>df -h</code></td><td>Free/used disk space, human-readable</td></tr><tr><td><code>du -h</code></td><td>Space consumed by files/folders</td></tr></tbody></table><p>For example, <code>sar -u 2 5</code> reports CPU utilization every 2 seconds, five times. Linux logs live under <code>/var/log</code> via <span class='keyterm'>rsyslog</span>; Windows logs live in Event Viewer. Both ecosystems can centralize logs for easier reporting, and logs are subject to retention rules (<code>logrotate</code> on Linux archives and compresses old logs; Windows can cap log size and overwrite oldest events).</p><h3>Why the Baseline Is Central</h3><p>The <span class='keyterm'>baseline</span> is the linchpin of all monitoring. Captured when the server first goes live, it documents normal CPU, memory, disk, and network behavior under known load. Every later reading is interpreted <em>against</em> it: a 70% CPU figure means nothing until you know the baseline was 30%. The same baseline reappears in the troubleshooting methodology — after implementing a fix you verify full system functionality by comparing performance to the original baseline. This is also why you monitor with a <strong>consistent</strong> counter set over time rather than ad-hoc metrics; consistency is what makes trend analysis and capacity planning possible. Watching the trend tells you when to add resources <em>before</em> users feel pain.</p><h3>Event Logs and System Uptime</h3><p>Windows <span class='keyterm'>Event Viewer</span> separates events into <strong>Application</strong> (program events), <strong>Security</strong> (auditing, logon success/failure), and <strong>System</strong> (Windows and service events) logs, with filtering to surface exactly what you need — a daily management and troubleshooting staple. <span class='keyterm'>System uptime</span> appears on the Task Manager Performance tab in Windows and via the <code>uptime</code> command in Linux, which also reports user count and 1/5/15-minute load averages. Unexpectedly low uptime can reveal an unplanned reboot or crash worth investigating in Reliability Monitor or the System log.</p><h3>Log Retention, Shipping, and Centralization</h3><p>Because logs record detailed events, industry or legal regulations often dictate how long they must be kept and how they are made available to auditors. Since old logs are rarely accessed, they can be compressed, archived, and moved to offline storage. Centralizing logs from many servers (via rsyslog forwarding or a Windows collector) makes correlation and reporting far easier. A distinct concept, <span class='keyterm'>log shipping</span>, applies to database servers like SQL Server or MySQL: transaction-log changes on a primary are continuously replayed on a secondary so that if the primary fails, the secondary takes over with little to no downtime — a monitoring-adjacent technique that boosts database availability.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A web server feels slow but CPU sits at 40%. Comparing to the <strong>baseline</strong>, you spot disk <strong>Average Queue Length</strong> far above normal and high <strong>IOPS</strong> wait. The storage subsystem, not the CPU, is the bottleneck — you move the site to faster disks and the metric returns to baseline.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div>Remember the <strong>80% CPU</strong> guideline and that <strong>IOPS</strong> measures disk performance. A rising <strong>disk queue length</strong> or high <strong>Pages/sec</strong> indicates a bottleneck. On Linux reach for <code>top</code>, <code>sar</code>, <code>uptime</code>, <code>df</code>, and <code>du</code>; always compare against the original <strong>baseline</strong>.</div>"}
);
SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Data Migration & Transfer", body:"<p>Servers continually move data — onto a new server during a migration, off an old one during decommissioning, or between systems for replication and backup. SK0-005 expects you to know the administrative tools, validate transfers, and plan downtime so the business is not blindsided. Legitimate transfers ride on file-sharing protocols like <span class='keyterm'>SMB</span> and <span class='keyterm'>NFS</span>, or on FTP and HTTP, and frequently cross OS boundaries (an HTTP download from a Linux web server to a Windows client, for example).</p><h3>Transfer Tools</h3><table><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Platform</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>Robocopy</span></td><td>Windows</td><td>Copies entire directory trees with permissions, attributes, ownership; does <strong>not</strong> encrypt the transfer</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>rsync</span></td><td>Linux</td><td>Can transfer only <em>changed</em> files in a tree, saving time and bandwidth</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>scp</span></td><td>Linux</td><td>Secure copy over SSH — encrypted, guarantees integrity and confidentiality</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>WinSCP</span></td><td>Windows&harr;Linux</td><td>GUI cross-platform tool; encrypts contents</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Example syntax: <code>robocopy D:\\data G:\\information</code> (source then destination); <code>rsync -azvh user@remote:/archive /home</code> (remote source to local destination); <code>scp user@remote:foo.txt /local/archive</code>. Because Robocopy does not encrypt, sensitive transfers across untrusted links should use scp or WinSCP instead.</p><h3>Migration Types</h3><p>When relocating whole servers, the classic options are <span class='keyterm'>P2V</span> (physical to virtual — very common when consolidating into virtualization or cloud), <span class='keyterm'>V2P</span> (virtual to physical), and <span class='keyterm'>V2V</span> (between hypervisor platforms). VM cloning and templating also move full configurations including OS, apps, and data.</p><h3>Validation</h3><p>A transfer is not done until you <strong>validate</strong> it. Validation confirms the destination data matches the source in count, size, and content — typically by comparing file counts and sizes and, more rigorously, by computing and comparing <span class='keyterm'>checksums/hashes</span> on both ends. For a server migration, validation also means functional testing: do services start, do applications connect, do permissions and ownership survive the copy? Tools like Robocopy preserve ACLs and attributes precisely so that validated permissions carry over. Skipping validation risks silent corruption or missing files that only surface later in production.</p><h3>Downtime Planning</h3><p>Migrations often require a service interruption, so plan it deliberately. Good practice: notify affected users in advance with an <strong>expected outage duration</strong>; schedule cutover during a <span class='keyterm'>maintenance window</span> (off-hours when files are unlikely to be open); back up data before starting if there is any risk; and define a rollback plan in case validation fails. Strategies that minimize downtime include pre-seeding the bulk of data ahead of time and using a final incremental sync (rsync's changed-files-only behavior shines here) so the cutover copy is small and fast. The principle from the troubleshooting methodology applies — avoid service interruptions and data loss, and make one controlled change at a time.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>You are moving a 4 TB file share to a new server. You rsync the bulk copy days early, then during a Saturday maintenance window run a final <code>rsync</code> to capture only changed files (minutes, not hours), validate file counts and checksums, confirm NTFS permissions transferred via Robocopy, and only then repoint clients.</div><h3>Transfer Protocols and Encryption</h3><p>Beyond the command-line tools, data moves over standard protocols. <span class='keyterm'>SMB</span> (Windows file sharing) and <span class='keyterm'>NFS</span> (Linux/Unix sharing) are the most common, and both can bridge disparate OSs. <span class='keyterm'>FTP</span> and <span class='keyterm'>HTTP/HTTPS</span> also move data, often between a Linux web server and Windows or macOS clients. The encryption distinction is exam-relevant: plain FTP and HTTP transmit in cleartext, while HTTPS, SFTP/SCP (over SSH), and WinSCP encrypt the payload. Robocopy preserves NTFS permissions and ownership but does <strong>not</strong> encrypt the wire, so for sensitive data crossing untrusted links you layer encryption (a VPN tunnel) or switch to an encrypting tool. Choosing the right protocol balances compatibility, performance, and confidentiality.</p><h3>Legitimate vs Illegitimate Transfers</h3><p>Not all data movement is authorized. <span class='keyterm'>Data exfiltration</span> is the unauthorized copying of content <em>off</em> a server in a breach — confidential HR files siphoned to an attacker's laptop, for example. <span class='keyterm'>Data infiltration</span> is unauthorized data sent <em>to</em> a server, such as ransomware delivered via a file transfer, though the term also covers legitimate inbound flows like a photographer uploading images to an FTP server or a database replicating in for redundancy. The same protocols that perform sanctioned migrations can be abused, which is why monitoring, logging, and least-privilege permissions on transfer paths matter as much as the transfer mechanics themselves.</p><h3>Planning, Backup, and Rollback</h3><p>A disciplined migration mirrors the troubleshooting methodology: avoid service interruptions and data loss, make controlled changes, and document each step. Before cutover you <strong>back up</strong> the source so a failed migration cannot destroy the only copy, and you define a <strong>rollback plan</strong> — the exact steps to revert clients to the old server if validation fails. Pre-seeding the bulk of data days ahead and finishing with a small incremental sync keeps the actual outage window short, and rsync's changed-files-only mode makes that final sync fast. Communicating the expected duration to users and scheduling the cutover in an off-hours maintenance window minimizes business impact while preserving a clean retreat path.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div>Know the tools by platform: <strong>Robocopy</strong> (Windows, preserves permissions, not encrypted), <strong>rsync</strong> (Linux, changed-files-only), <strong>scp/WinSCP</strong> (encrypted). Always <strong>validate</strong> with hashes/checksums and plan a <strong>maintenance window</strong> with user notification, a pre-cutover backup, and a rollback plan. Distinguish <strong>exfiltration</strong> (data out, breach) from <strong>infiltration</strong> (data in).</div>"}
);
SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Clustering & High Availability", body:"<p>A core goal of security and operations is <span class='keyterm'>availability</span>, and <span class='keyterm'>high availability (HA)</span> means designing so that the failure of any single component does not take the service down. <span class='keyterm'>Clustering</span> is the primary HA technique: two or more servers (<span class='keyterm'>nodes</span>) are joined into a <span class='keyterm'>cluster</span> that presents itself to clients as a single logical service. If a node fails, the workload continues on a surviving node, ideally with little or no interruption. Clustering complements, but is distinct from, simple hardware redundancy (redundant NICs, power supplies, RAID) within one box — a cluster protects against the loss of an entire server.</p><h3>Active/Active vs Active/Passive</h3><p>Clusters operate in one of two fundamental modes:</p><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>Active/Active</th><th>Active/Passive</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Node usage</td><td>All nodes serve workload</td><td>One node active, other(s) standby</td></tr><tr><td>Resource efficiency</td><td>High &mdash; no idle hardware</td><td>Lower &mdash; standby sits ready</td></tr><tr><td>On failure</td><td>Survivors absorb extra load</td><td>Standby takes over the role</td></tr><tr><td>Performance risk</td><td>Survivors may be overloaded</td><td>Standby has full capacity</td></tr><tr><td>Typical use</td><td>Load-shared web/app tiers</td><td>Databases, critical single-instance roles</td></tr></tbody></table><p>In <span class='keyterm'>active/active</span>, every node processes requests simultaneously, maximizing hardware use and naturally distributing load — but if one node dies, the remaining nodes must shoulder the full load, which can degrade performance unless capacity was reserved. In <span class='keyterm'>active/passive</span>, one node runs the service while a passive standby waits idle; on failure the passive node takes over (a <span class='keyterm'>failover</span>). This wastes some capacity but guarantees the survivor can handle 100% of the load.</p><h3>Quorum and Split-Brain</h3><p>A cluster must agree on which nodes are healthy and who owns the workload, or two nodes might both try to run the same service against the same storage — a dangerous condition called <span class='keyterm'>split-brain</span> that corrupts data. The mechanism that prevents this is <span class='keyterm'>quorum</span>: the cluster requires a majority of votes to remain operational. Each node typically gets a vote, and a tie-breaker — a <span class='keyterm'>witness</span> (a shared disk or a file-share/cloud witness) — provides an extra vote so an even-numbered cluster can still form a majority. If a node loses contact and cannot reach quorum, it stops serving rather than risk split-brain. Shared storage (often on a clustered file system such as VMFS) lets whichever node owns the role read and write the same data.</p><h3>Shared Components and Heartbeat</h3><p>Cluster nodes monitor each other with a <span class='keyterm'>heartbeat</span> — periodic health signals over a dedicated network. Missed heartbeats trigger the failover logic. Clients reach the cluster through a virtual IP or virtual name that follows the active node, so the client experience is unaffected by which physical node is currently serving.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A two-node SQL cluster runs active/passive on shared storage with a <strong>file-share witness</strong> as the third quorum vote. When the active node's heartbeat stops, the cluster confirms quorum via the witness, fails the database role over to the passive node, and the virtual name redirects clients — downtime is seconds, and split-brain is prevented because only the quorum-holding node serves.</div><h3>HA Versus Simple Redundancy</h3><p>It is important to separate two layers of protection. <span class='keyterm'>Hardware redundancy</span> within one box — redundant power supplies, teamed NICs, RAID arrays — protects against the failure of a <em>component</em>. <span class='keyterm'>Clustering</span> protects against the failure of an entire <em>server</em>, including its OS, motherboard, or a software crash that a redundant power supply could never address. Both belong in a high-availability design: you build each node with redundant internals <em>and</em> cluster the nodes so no single server is a point of failure. Virtualization adds a third dimension — replicating VMs between hosts so that if a whole hypervisor host dies, a survivor holds a current copy of every guest. Layering these defenses is how organizations approach the 'five nines' of availability.</p><h3>Shared Storage and the Virtual Identity</h3><p>For a cluster to fail a workload over, the surviving node must reach the same data. This is why clusters rely on <span class='keyterm'>shared storage</span> — a SAN volume or a clustered file system such as VMFS — that whichever node currently owns the role can read and write. Clients never address the physical nodes directly; instead they connect to a <span class='keyterm'>virtual IP</span> and virtual name that float to whichever node is active. When failover occurs, the virtual identity moves to the survivor and clients reconnect to the same address, often without noticing more than a brief pause. Without shared storage and a floating identity, a 'cluster' would just be two separate servers.</p><h3>Measuring and Tuning Availability</h3><p>Availability is quantified by <span class='keyterm'>uptime</span> percentage and by recovery objectives. Two terms frame recovery: the <span class='keyterm'>Recovery Time Objective (RTO)</span> is how quickly service must be restored, and the <span class='keyterm'>Recovery Point Objective (RPO)</span> is how much data loss is tolerable, measured in time. Active/passive failover with shared storage targets a very short RTO and near-zero RPO. Heartbeat tuning matters too: too-aggressive heartbeat timeouts cause needless failovers on transient blips, while too-lax timeouts delay legitimate failover. Administrators tune heartbeat intervals and quorum settings to balance responsiveness against stability.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div><strong>Active/active</strong> uses all nodes (efficient, but survivors may overload); <strong>active/passive</strong> keeps a standby (wastes capacity, guarantees performance). <strong>Quorum</strong> (often with a <strong>witness</strong>) prevents <strong>split-brain</strong> in even-node clusters. Clusters need <strong>shared storage</strong> and a floating <strong>virtual IP/name</strong>; HA layers hardware redundancy, clustering, and VM replication together.</div>"}
);
SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Load Balancing & Failover", body:"<p>Where clustering keeps a service alive through node failure, <span class='keyterm'>load balancing</span> distributes incoming work across multiple servers so no single server is overwhelmed and so capacity scales horizontally. The two concepts overlap — a load-balanced pool inherently provides fault tolerance because a failed member is simply removed from rotation — but the emphasis differs: clustering targets <em>availability</em>, load balancing targets <em>distribution and scale</em>.</p><h3>Load-Balancing Algorithms</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>load balancer</span> (hardware appliance, software, or a cloud service) sits in front of a server pool and decides which backend handles each request according to an algorithm:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Algorithm</th><th>How it distributes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>Round robin</span></td><td>Each new request to the next server in sequence, cycling through the pool</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>Weighted round robin</span></td><td>Round robin, but more powerful servers get a larger share</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>Least connections</span></td><td>Sends to the server with the fewest active connections</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>Weighted least connections</span></td><td>Least connections adjusted for server capacity</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>Source IP hash</span></td><td>Hashes client IP so a client consistently hits the same server</td></tr></tbody></table><p><span class='keyterm'>Session persistence</span> (or <span class='keyterm'>affinity / sticky sessions</span>) ensures a client stays bound to the same backend for the duration of a session — essential when application state lives on the server (a shopping cart, for instance) rather than in shared storage.</p><h3>Health Checks and the Heartbeat</h3><p>A load balancer constantly probes each backend with <span class='keyterm'>health checks</span> (much like a cluster's <span class='keyterm'>heartbeat</span>). A member that fails its check is pulled from the pool so no new requests are sent to a dead server; when it recovers and passes checks again, it is returned to rotation. This automatic removal and re-addition is what makes load balancing fault-tolerant.</p><h3>Failover and Fault Tolerance</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Failover</span> is the automatic shift of work from a failed resource to a healthy one. It can be active/active (load shared, survivors absorb the load) or active/passive (a standby takes over). <span class='keyterm'>Fault tolerance</span> is the broader property of continuing to operate despite component failure, achieved by eliminating <span class='keyterm'>single points of failure</span> at every layer — redundant NICs and teaming, redundant power supplies, RAID for disks, clustered nodes, and even redundant load balancers (an active/passive pair) so the balancer itself is not a single point of failure. A virtual IP that floats between balancer or server nodes lets clients keep using one address regardless of which physical device is serving.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Concept</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Load balancing</td><td>Distribute requests, scale horizontally</td></tr><tr><td>Health check / heartbeat</td><td>Detect dead members, remove/re-add</td></tr><tr><td>Session persistence</td><td>Keep a client on one backend</td></tr><tr><td>Failover</td><td>Auto-shift work to a healthy resource</td></tr><tr><td>Fault tolerance</td><td>Eliminate single points of failure</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>Three web servers sit behind a load balancer using <strong>least connections</strong> with <strong>sticky sessions</strong> so users keep their shopping carts. When server 2 stops answering health checks, the balancer drops it from the pool; traffic continues seamlessly across servers 1 and 3, and server 2 rejoins automatically once healthy.</div><h3>Where Load Balancers Sit</h3><p>A load balancer can be a dedicated hardware appliance, a software service, or a cloud-managed offering, and it terminates client connections at a single front-end address before distributing them to the pool behind it. Layer-4 balancers make decisions on IP and port alone (fast, protocol-agnostic), while layer-7 balancers inspect application data such as HTTP headers and URLs, enabling content-aware routing (sending <code>/images</code> to one pool and <code>/api</code> to another). Many enterprise load balancers also offload work from the backends — terminating TLS, caching responses, and compressing content — so the application servers can focus on application logic. This front-end placement is also what lets the balancer present one stable virtual IP no matter how the pool behind it changes.</p><h3>Scaling Out vs Scaling Up</h3><p>Load balancing enables <span class='keyterm'>horizontal scaling</span> (scale out) — adding more servers to the pool to handle growth — as opposed to <span class='keyterm'>vertical scaling</span> (scale up), which means making a single server bigger. Scaling out is attractive because it adds both capacity and redundancy at once and avoids the ceiling of a single machine, but it requires that application state live in shared storage or a shared session store rather than on individual servers; otherwise session persistence becomes mandatory to keep users on the server holding their state. This trade-off between stateless scale-out and stateful affinity is a core design decision.</p><h3>Eliminating Single Points of Failure End to End</h3><p>True fault tolerance examines every layer for a single point of failure. The backends are pooled, but the load balancer itself must not be the weak link, so it is typically deployed as a redundant <strong>active/passive pair</strong> sharing a virtual IP via a heartbeat — if the active balancer dies, the standby assumes the VIP. Network paths are made redundant with teamed NICs and multiple switches, power with dual supplies on separate circuits, and storage with RAID and clustered volumes. The discipline is to walk the request path and ask, at each hop, 'what happens if this one thing fails?' — then add redundancy until no single failure can take the service down.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div>Know the algorithms — <strong>round robin</strong> (sequential), <strong>least connections</strong> (fewest active), <strong>weighted</strong> (capacity-aware), <strong>source-IP hash</strong> (consistent client mapping). <strong>Heartbeat/health checks</strong> drive failover; <strong>fault tolerance</strong> means no single point of failure — including a redundant balancer pair. Load balancing enables horizontal <strong>scale-out</strong>.</div>"}
);
SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Virtualization — Hypervisors Type 1/2, Host vs Guest", body:"<p>Objective <strong>2.5</strong> asks you to summarize the purpose and operation of virtualization. Virtualization lets one powerful physical server run many independent virtual servers, ending the era of one-OS-per-box. Instead of predicting demand and buying dedicated hardware that often sits idle, organizations run a few strong hosts carrying many <span class='keyterm'>virtual machines (VMs)</span>, dramatically improving hardware efficiency, scalability, and agility.</p><h3>Host vs Guest</h3><p>Virtualization starts with one physical server, the <span class='keyterm'>host system</span> — usually powerful, with redundant hardware for performance and availability. A software layer called the <span class='keyterm'>hypervisor</span> is added to the host; it allocates the host's resources to the VMs. The VMs themselves are the <span class='keyterm'>guest systems</span> (guests) — each is allocated a slice of CPU time, RAM, storage, and network, then has its own OS and applications installed. A guest looks and behaves like an independent physical computer, with its own MAC and IP via a <span class='keyterm'>vNIC</span> attached to a virtual switch.</p><h3>Type 1 vs Type 2 Hypervisors</h3><p>The single most tested virtualization fact is the difference between the two hypervisor types:</p><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>Type 1 (bare-metal)</th><th>Type 2 (hosted)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Installed on</td><td>Directly on hardware</td><td>On top of a host OS</td></tr><tr><td>OS layer</td><td>None &mdash; hypervisor <em>is</em> the OS</td><td>Runs inside Windows/Linux/macOS</td></tr><tr><td>Performance</td><td>Higher, less overhead</td><td>Lower, OS overhead</td></tr><tr><td>Examples</td><td>VMware ESXi, Microsoft Hyper-V, KVM</td><td>Oracle VirtualBox, VMware Workstation</td></tr><tr><td>Typical use</td><td>Enterprise/production hosts</td><td>Dev, test, labs, workstations</td></tr></tbody></table><p>A <span class='keyterm'>Type 1</span> hypervisor installs <strong>directly on the physical server</strong> with no traditional OS beneath it — the hypervisor acts as its own thin OS. This minimizes overhead and is why ESXi, Hyper-V, and KVM dominate enterprise virtualization, typically bundling HA and clustering features. A <span class='keyterm'>Type 2</span> hypervisor runs as an application <strong>inside a conventional host OS</strong>; VirtualBox and VMware Workstation are the classic examples. Type 2 suits developers, students, and admins doing testing — even on ordinary workstation hardware — but carries the extra overhead of the underlying OS, making it unsuitable for heavy production.</p><h3>Redundancy and High Availability</h3><p>A lone virtualization host is a <span class='keyterm'>single point of failure</span>: if it dies, every guest on it dies too. Therefore HA is essential — most enterprise solutions can <strong>replicate VMs</strong> between two or more hosts so a survivor holds a current copy, and hosts are built with redundant NICs, power supplies, and disks. VMs may have several network modes: <strong>none</strong>, <strong>local</strong> (only other VMs on the host), <strong>host-only</strong> (only the host, not the physical network), and <strong>bridged</strong> (full access to the physical network/Internet, used for production VMs like DNS or web servers). NAT in the hypervisor lets internal vNICs reach the Internet.</p><h3>Management</h3><p>Type 2 hypervisors offer a simple local console; enterprise Type 1 platforms use centralized consoles — Microsoft's Hyper-V console and VMware's <span class='keyterm'>vSphere</span> — installed on an admin workstation to manage many hosts remotely, plus command-line management for automation.</p><h3>Why Virtualization Won</h3><p>Before virtualization, organizations had to forecast utilization, buy dedicated hardware for each workload, and manage the physical lifecycle of every box — a model that was neither agile nor scalable, and that left expensive processors idle much of the time. Virtualization decouples the workload from the hardware: many VMs share a few powerful hosts, hardware utilization climbs dramatically, and new servers appear in minutes from templates rather than weeks from purchase orders. It is increasingly hard to justify the cost and maintenance of one-OS-per-box deployments. This consolidation is also what makes cloud computing possible, since cloud servers are themselves VMs running in a provider's data center.</p><h3>The Hypervisor's Job</h3><p>The hypervisor is the software layer that sits between hardware and guests and arbitrates access to the physical resources. It schedules vCPUs onto physical cores, hands out RAM, presents virtual disks backed by host storage, and bridges vNICs to physical or virtual networks. Because the hypervisor mediates everything, it can over-allocate idle resources, snapshot a running VM, migrate a live VM to another host, and enforce isolation so one guest cannot read another's memory. A Type 1 hypervisor performs these duties with minimal overhead because nothing stands between it and the hardware; a Type 2 hypervisor must route the same operations through its host OS, adding latency that rules it out for demanding production loads.</p><h3>Management and Networking</h3><p>Enterprise Type 1 platforms are administered through centralized consoles installed on an admin workstation — Microsoft's Hyper-V Manager and VMware's <span class='keyterm'>vSphere</span> — which connect to many hosts at once and enable features like live migration and clustering, plus command-line and API automation for consistent, scheduled management. Type 2 products ship a simpler local console for the VMs on that one machine. On the network side, each guest's vNIC carries its own MAC and IP and attaches to a virtual switch, can join a VLAN, and reaches the outside world through bridging or hypervisor NAT — so from a client's perspective a bridged production VM is indistinguishable from a physical server.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A developer needs an isolated test lab on her laptop, so she installs <strong>VirtualBox</strong> (Type 2) and spins up a few VMs in host-only mode. Meanwhile the data center runs the production tier on <strong>ESXi</strong> (Type 1) clustered across three hosts with VM replication, so a host failure never takes the application down.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div>Type 1 = <strong>bare-metal</strong>, directly on hardware (ESXi, Hyper-V, KVM), for production. Type 2 = <strong>hosted</strong> inside an OS (VirtualBox, VMware Workstation), for testing. The <strong>host</strong> runs the hypervisor; the <strong>guests</strong> are the VMs. A single host is a single point of failure — replicate for HA.</div>"}
);
SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Resource Allocation & VM Management", body:"<p>Virtualization carves a host's physical resources into slices for each guest, much like specifying hardware when buying a physical server. If a host has 64 GB of RAM, you might allocate 16 GB to one VM and 8 GB to another, leaving 40 GB for additional guests — and the same partitioning applies to CPU, storage, and network. Crucially, <strong>some resources must stay unallocated</strong> for the host hypervisor itself. Managing these allocations well is what keeps a dense virtualization platform performant.</p><h3>vCPU and Virtual Memory</h3><p>A guest is assigned <span class='keyterm'>virtual CPUs (vCPUs)</span> that map to the host's physical cores and threads, and a quantity of RAM. Allocation is dynamic: during early testing a VM may get a few users and minimal resources, then receive more CPU and memory as it scales to enterprise use. The administrator tunes these to match real demand discovered through monitoring.</p><h3>Overprovisioning and Overcommit</h3><p>Two related but distinct ideas appear here. <span class='keyterm'>Overprovisioning</span> means equipping the host with <em>more</em> physical hardware than current need requires — for example installing multiple teamed NICs so combined bandwidth exceeds anticipated demand, giving headroom for growth. <span class='keyterm'>Overcommit (over-allocation)</span> means deliberately promising VMs <em>more</em> virtual resources than the host physically has, betting that not all VMs peak simultaneously. Because many server CPUs sit idle much of the time, overcommitting vCPUs can dramatically improve overall utilization. But it is risky without data: if too many VMs demand resources at once, the host and every guest suffer. Sound overcommit requires careful, continuous monitoring to understand each VM's true CPU, memory, and timing requirements.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Concept</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Risk/benefit</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Allocation</td><td>Assign a fixed slice to a VM</td><td>Predictable, may waste idle capacity</td></tr><tr><td>Overprovision</td><td>Host has more hardware than needed</td><td>Headroom for growth/HA</td></tr><tr><td>Overcommit</td><td>VMs promised more than host has</td><td>Higher utilization, contention risk</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Snapshots, Clones, and Templates</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>snapshot</span> captures a VM's state — disk, memory, and configuration — at a point in time, letting you instantly roll back if a patch or change goes wrong. Snapshots are invaluable before risky maintenance but are <strong>not backups</strong>: they live on the same storage as the VM and grow over time, degrading performance if left in place, so they should be short-lived. A <span class='keyterm'>clone</span> is a full independent copy of a VM (because a VM is essentially a configuration file plus virtual disks), useful for spinning up identical instances. A <span class='keyterm'>template</span> is a pre-built, generalized VM configuration used for self-service provisioning: an admin builds a template meeting a developer's needs, and the developer deploys VMs from it on demand without waiting.</p><h3>Virtual Networking and Storage</h3><p>Each guest's vNIC has its own MAC and IP and attaches to a virtual switch; guests can join VLANs and use NAT or bridging exactly like physical hosts. Virtual disks draw from the host's storage pool (often a clustered file system such as VMFS), and resources can be reallocated dynamically as business needs change.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>Before applying a major update to an application VM, you take a <strong>snapshot</strong>. The patch breaks the app, so you revert to the snapshot in seconds — then delete the snapshot afterward so it does not bloat storage. For the next ten test VMs, you deploy from a <strong>template</strong> rather than building each by hand.</div><h3>Reserving Resources for the Host</h3><p>A frequently missed rule is that you cannot allocate <em>all</em> of a host's resources to guests — the hypervisor itself needs CPU, RAM, and storage to function. Over-allocating to the point of starving the host degrades every VM simultaneously, since the layer scheduling them all is the one being squeezed. Sound capacity planning therefore reserves a margin for the host and leaves headroom for failover: in a cluster you size hosts so that if one fails, the survivors can absorb its VMs without breaching their own limits (this is the 'N+1' idea). Dynamic allocation lets you grow a VM's resources as demand rises — a few users during testing, far more after enterprise rollout — but those increases must respect the host's real ceiling.</p><h3>Monitoring to Justify Overcommit</h3><p>Overcommit is powerful but data-driven. Because many server CPUs idle most of the time, promising more vCPUs than physical cores raises utilization without harm — <em>as long as</em> the VMs do not peak together. The only way to know is sustained monitoring of each guest's actual CPU, memory, disk, and network usage and the timing of its peaks. Memory overcommit is riskier than CPU overcommit because RAM is harder to reclaim transparently; when a host runs short it may resort to swapping VM memory to disk, collapsing performance. The discipline is to overcommit conservatively, watch for contention signals (high CPU-ready time, ballooning, host swapping), and dial back before users feel it.</p><h3>Snapshot Hygiene and Cloning</h3><p>Snapshots deserve operational care. A snapshot freezes a VM's disk, memory, and configuration so you can revert instantly after a risky change, but every snapshot accumulates a delta file that grows as the VM writes data; left in place, a chain of old snapshots consumes storage and slows I/O. Best practice is to snapshot immediately before a change and delete it once the change is validated — never treat snapshots as backups, since they live on the same storage as the VM and vanish with it. <span class='keyterm'>Cloning</span> produces a full, independent copy for a new instance, and <span class='keyterm'>templates</span> generalize a configuration for repeatable, self-service provisioning so developers deploy standardized VMs on demand without waiting on an administrator.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div>Distinguish <strong>overprovision</strong> (more physical hardware than needed) from <strong>overcommit/over-allocate</strong> (promising VMs more virtual resources than exist). Always reserve resources for the <strong>host</strong> and leave failover headroom. <strong>Snapshots</strong> enable quick rollback but are <strong>not backups</strong> and must be short-lived. <strong>Templates</strong> drive consistent self-service deployment.</div>"}
);
SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Cloud Models — IaaS/PaaS/SaaS, Public/Private/Hybrid", body:"<p>Cloud computing extends virtualization: cloud servers are still VMs, but they run in a <span class='keyterm'>cloud service provider (CSP)</span> data center rather than on your premises, offloading parts of the server lifecycle to the provider. NIST defines five essential cloud characteristics: <strong>on-demand self-service</strong>, <strong>broad network access</strong>, <strong>resource pooling</strong>, <strong>rapid elasticity</strong>, and <strong>measured service</strong> (pay for what you use).</p><h3>Deployment Models</h3><p>Deployment models define <em>who owns and operates</em> the underlying data center:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>Who owns it</th><th>Trade-off</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>Private</span></td><td>One organization, exclusive</td><td>Strong security/control, but expensive</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>Public</span></td><td>A CSP, shared by many tenants</td><td>Cost-effective, less data control</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>Community</span></td><td>Several like-minded orgs share</td><td>Shared cost, higher security than public</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>Hybrid</span></td><td>Any mix of the above</td><td>Sensitive data private, rest public</td></tr></tbody></table><p>A <span class='keyterm'>private cloud</span> serves a single organization exclusively — maximum control and data isolation at high cost. A <span class='keyterm'>public cloud</span> (AWS, Azure, GCP) shares pooled resources across customers for big cost savings with somewhat reduced control. A <span class='keyterm'>community cloud</span> is shared among organizations with similar requirements, splitting cost while keeping security higher than public. A <span class='keyterm'>hybrid cloud</span> blends them — for instance keeping regulated data on-premises/private while using a public SaaS suite — to capture each model's strengths.</p><h3>Service Models</h3><p>Service models define <em>how much</em> the CSP manages versus the customer. The clearest way to remember them is by target audience:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>CSP manages</th><th>You manage</th><th>Audience</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>IaaS</span></td><td>Hardware, virtualization</td><td>OS, apps, data</td><td>Sysadmins</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>PaaS</span></td><td>Hardware, OS, runtime/platform</td><td>Your apps & data</td><td>Developers, DBAs</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>SaaS</span></td><td>Everything up to the app</td><td>Just use it (data/config)</td><td>End users</td></tr></tbody></table><p><span class='keyterm'>Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)</span> rents VMs/hardware — you install and maintain the OS and applications (AWS EC2, Azure, Rackspace). <span class='keyterm'>Platform as a Service (PaaS)</span> provides a ready platform such as a database or dev environment you build upon while the CSP handles hardware and OS (AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Google App Engine). <span class='keyterm'>Software as a Service (SaaS)</span> delivers finished software with the vendor handling everything — installation, patching, hardware, OS (Office 365, Google Docs, Netflix).</p><h3>Shared Responsibility</h3><p>The <span class='keyterm'>shared security/responsibility model</span> divides duties: the CSP secures the cloud infrastructure (physical data center, hardware availability — 'security <em>of</em> the cloud'), while the customer secures their data and access ('security <em>in</em> the cloud'). The more of the stack the CSP manages (SaaS most, IaaS least), the more responsibility shifts to the provider.</p><h3>The Five Essential Characteristics in Depth</h3><p>NIST's five traits explain <em>why</em> cloud changed IT economics. <strong>On-demand self-service</strong> lets a consumer provision resources instantly without phoning the provider. <strong>Broad network access</strong> makes services reachable from phones, tablets, laptops, and servers over the network. <strong>Resource pooling</strong> means the provider's compute, storage, and network are pooled and dynamically assigned to many tenants, who generally do not know the physical location of their resources. <strong>Rapid elasticity</strong> scales capacity up and down to match load, so you pay only for what you need at any moment. <strong>Measured service</strong> meters utilization and bills on actual use. Together these shift spending from large up-front <span class='keyterm'>capital expenditure (CapEx)</span> toward pay-as-you-go <span class='keyterm'>operational expenditure (OpEx)</span>, change the skill set sysadmins need, and offload hardware maintenance to the provider.</p><h3>The Major Providers</h3><p>Three CSPs dominate and all satisfy every service model: <span class='keyterm'>Amazon Web Services (AWS)</span> (hosted on Linux, supports Linux and Windows VMs; EC2 is its IaaS), <span class='keyterm'>Microsoft Azure</span> (Windows-hosted, supports both VM types), and <span class='keyterm'>Google Cloud Platform (GCP)</span>. Each runs data centers worldwide, enabling <span class='keyterm'>geo-redundancy</span> that replicates data across regions for availability and places it nearer to dispersed users. Many CSPs hold certifications for PII handling, PCI DSS, FERPA, and other standards, which can actually <em>ease</em> compliance for customers who would struggle to certify their own data centers.</p><h3>On-Premises vs Cloud Trade-Offs</h3><p>Choosing between on-premises and cloud is a recurring decision. On-premises deployments — physical or virtual — give complete control over environment, administration, and data, support specialized hardware, and may keep data nearer to users, but the organization bears the full cost of hardware, installation, maintenance, personnel, and security, faces higher CapEx, scales slowly, and deploys slowly. Cloud deployments charge only for consumed resources, offload service support, simplify licensing, scale and deploy quickly, and add geo-redundancy, but the organization cedes control of the environment, may lose access during an Internet or CSP outage, can see rising OpEx, and may store data farther from users. Small and mid-size organizations often favor cloud for its flexibility and low entry cost, while firms with unique or strict security requirements keep sensitive systems on-premises — frequently arriving at a <strong>hybrid</strong> design that plays each model to its strengths.</p><h3>Beyond the Big Three: the XaaS Family</h3><p>The service model spectrum extends well past IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS into a broader <span class='keyterm'>XaaS</span> ('anything as a service') family the exam may reference. <span class='keyterm'>Disaster Recovery as a Service (DRaaS)</span> continuously replicates production servers to a provider that can spin them up on demand, shrinking recovery time without the cost of a second data center. <span class='keyterm'>Function as a Service (FaaS)</span>, or serverless computing, runs short-lived event-triggered code with no server for the customer to patch or size, billing per execution. <span class='keyterm'>Desktop as a Service (DaaS)</span> streams managed virtual desktops to thin clients. A related hybrid pattern, <span class='keyterm'>cloud bursting</span>, runs a workload in a private cloud and temporarily 'bursts' overflow demand into a public cloud during spikes — capping on-premises capital cost while still absorbing peak load.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div>Audience mnemonic: <strong>IaaS = sysadmins</strong>, <strong>PaaS = developers/DBAs</strong>, <strong>SaaS = end users</strong>. Deployment = <em>who owns the data center</em> (private/public/community/hybrid); service = <em>how much the CSP manages</em>. Know the five NIST traits, CapEx-vs-OpEx, and that in the shared model the CSP secures the cloud while you secure your data in it.</div>"}
);
SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Scripting Basics for Server Tasks", body:"<p>Objective <strong>2.6</strong> covers scripting basics for server administration. A <span class='keyterm'>script</span> is a text file of commands and system calls that automates administrative tasks. The workflow is simple: write commands into a file, give it execute permission, run it manually or on a schedule, and the system executes each command in order. Scripts deliver four big wins — they are <strong>consistent</strong> (the same steps run identically every time, no skipped or duplicated steps, no typos), <strong>fast</strong> (faster than typing), <strong>schedulable</strong> (via <span class='keyterm'>cron</span> on Linux or <span class='keyterm'>Task Scheduler</span> on Windows, e.g. a 2 a.m. backup), and <strong>adaptive</strong> (they branch on input or discovered results).</p><h3>Shell Languages: PowerShell and Bash</h3><p>Scripts are written in a <span class='keyterm'>shell</span> language and run only in a matching shell. The Linux default shell is <span class='keyterm'>bash</span>; Windows offers cmd.exe and the strongly preferred <span class='keyterm'>PowerShell</span>, whose commands are called <span class='keyterm'>cmdlets</span>. A PowerShell script will not run in bash and vice versa, so the right interpreter must be installed.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Script type</th><th>Language</th><th>Platform</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Batch (.bat)</td><td>MS-DOS commands</td><td>Windows, limited</td></tr><tr><td>Bash (.sh)</td><td>bash</td><td>Linux</td></tr><tr><td>PowerShell (.ps1)</td><td>cmdlets</td><td>Windows</td></tr><tr><td>VBScript (.vbs)</td><td>VBScript (deprecated)</td><td>Windows, legacy</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Comments and Variables</h3><p>Lines beginning with <code>#</code> are <span class='keyterm'>comments</span> — ignored by the system but vital for documenting scripts that others (or future you) will read. <span class='keyterm'>Variables</span> store values that may change by system, user, or time. <span class='keyterm'>Shell variables</span> are local to one shell instance; <span class='keyterm'>environment variables</span> are system-wide. Common bash environment variables include <code>$HOSTNAME</code>, <code>$USER</code> (current user), and <code>$HOME</code> (user's home directory). Referencing <code>$USER</code> instead of a hard-coded name lets one script work for any logged-in user.</p><h3>Constructs: Loops, Conditionals, Comparators</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Loops</span> repeat code. Bash has four: <strong>for</strong> (repeat a set number of times), <strong>while</strong> (repeat while a condition is true), <strong>until</strong> (repeat while a condition is false), and <strong>select</strong> (menu prompt). <span class='keyterm'>Conditionals</span> branch on truth: <code>if</code> runs its block when true, <code>else</code> when false. <span class='keyterm'>Comparators</span> compare values:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Operator</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>-eq</code> / <code>-ne</code></td><td>equal / not equal</td></tr><tr><td><code>-gt</code> / <code>-ge</code></td><td>greater than / greater-or-equal</td></tr><tr><td><code>-lt</code> / <code>-le</code></td><td>less than / less-or-equal</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Data Types and Functions</h3><p>Basic <span class='keyterm'>data types</span> are <strong>integers</strong> (whole numbers for math/comparison — <code>echo $((2+2))</code> prints 4), <strong>strings</strong> (alphanumeric text, e.g. searching files for 'sept'), and <strong>arrays</strong> (ordered lists, efficient for many values like 100 computer names). <span class='keyterm'>Functions</span> are named, reusable blocks of code called elsewhere in the script — for example a user-creation function invoked once per new account.</p><h3>Common Administrative Scripts</h3><p>Scripts run as <strong>login/logout</strong> scripts (map drives, launch apps, clean temp files), <strong>startup/shutdown</strong> scripts (check updates, apply security config, copy data), <strong>account management</strong> scripts (bulk-create users/groups/directories), and <strong>service</strong> scripts (restart several related services with one command).</p><h3>The Four Advantages, Concretely</h3><p>Consider a five-step backup. Run manually, you might be interrupted and skip a step, repeat one, or fat-finger a path. Scripted, the five steps run identically every time because you wrote and double-checked them once — that is <strong>consistency</strong>. The script also executes far faster than you can type, and the gain compounds as scripts grow longer — that is <strong>speed</strong>. You do not want to run a backup by hand at 2 a.m., so cron or Task Scheduler fires it automatically — that is <strong>scheduling</strong>. Finally, a script can branch: check a directory, delete it if empty, back it up if it has files — adapting its behavior to discovered conditions. These four properties are why scripting is a core sysadmin skill rather than a convenience.</p><h3>Why the Right Shell Matters</h3><p>A script is only understood by a shell that speaks its language, and that interpreter must be installed. A bash script will not run under PowerShell, and a PowerShell script will not run under bash — the syntax, command names, and even comment handling differ. This is also why platform matters: PowerShell scripts target Windows, bash scripts target Linux, batch files are legacy Windows, and VBScript is deprecated Windows. When you inherit or share a script, the first questions are which shell it was written for and whether that shell exists on the target. Because scripts are widely shared among admins and across the Internet, generous use of <code>#</code> comments documenting intent, examples, and gotchas is considered best practice for the next person who reads it.</p><h3>From Simple Commands to Real Logic</h3><p>Scripts start as plain command lists but gain real power from constructs and data. <span class='keyterm'>Functions</span> bundle a named block — say, every command needed to create and configure a user account — so it can be invoked repeatedly. <span class='keyterm'>Variables</span> like <code>$USER</code> or <code>$HOME</code> let one script adapt to whoever runs it. <span class='keyterm'>Arrays</span> hold many values efficiently — 100 computer names in one structure rather than 100 separate variables. Combine loops, conditionals, comparators, and functions and a script can iterate over an array of usernames, test each with an <code>if</code>, and call a creation function — automating what would be hours of error-prone manual work. This is exactly the kind of account-management, service-management, login/logout, and startup/shutdown automation administrators write daily.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>You must create the same ten accounts and lab directories on twenty classroom PCs. A <strong>bash</strong> script loops through an <strong>array</strong> of usernames, calls a <code>useradd</code> function for each, sets permissions, and creates home folders — one command provisions the whole lab consistently, and you schedule it to run before each new term.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div><strong>PowerShell = Windows</strong> (cmdlets), <strong>bash = Linux</strong>. <code>#</code> starts a comment. Know the loop types (for/while/until/select), if/else conditionals, and comparators (<code>-eq</code>, <code>-ne</code>, <code>-gt</code>, <code>-lt</code>). Data types: integer, string, array; <strong>functions</strong> are named reusable blocks. Schedule scripts with <strong>cron</strong> (Linux) or <strong>Task Scheduler</strong> (Windows).</div>"}
);
SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Asset Management & Lifecycle", body:"<p>Objective <strong>2.7</strong> covers asset management. A systems administrator is responsible for hardware and software throughout the <span class='keyterm'>server lifecycle</span>, conventionally four phases: <strong>procurement</strong>, <strong>usage</strong> (deployment and ongoing operation), <strong>end of life</strong>, and <strong>disposal/recycling</strong>. Deploying a new server is informally called 'standing up' the server. Tracking every asset across these phases — knowing what you own, where it is, how it is configured, and when it must be retired — is the heart of asset management.</p><h3>The Lifecycle Phases</h3><table><thead><tr><th>Phase</th><th>Activities</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Procurement</td><td>Specify requirements, purchase, verify against the OS HCL, receive and tag</td></tr><tr><td>Deployment</td><td>Install/configure, baseline performance, document, place into service</td></tr><tr><td>Usage / maintenance</td><td>Monitor, patch, repair, track warranty and support</td></tr><tr><td>End of life</td><td>Identify obsolescence/expiry, plan replacement, migrate workloads</td></tr><tr><td>Disposal / recycling</td><td>Sanitize data, decommission, recycle or destroy responsibly</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Tracking and Tagging Assets</h3><p>Each physical asset is typically given an <span class='keyterm'>asset tag</span> and recorded with details such as serial number, model, location, owner, purchase date, and warranty expiration. Tags may be barcodes or RFID for fast inventory. This inventory underpins capacity planning, warranty claims, audits, and replacement scheduling. Software assets are tracked too, which ties asset management to <strong>licensing</strong>: the organization must be able to prove <span class='keyterm'>license compliance</span> in an audit. License count validation demonstrates that installations or users match what was purchased; exceeding the count requires 'truing up' by buying additional licenses. License models the exam expects you to recognize include subscription, volume, per-instance, per-seat, per-concurrent-user, per-server (CALs), per-socket, and per-core.</p><h3>The CMDB</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>Configuration Management Database (CMDB)</span> is the central repository that stores <span class='keyterm'>configuration items (CIs)</span> — servers, applications, network devices, and the relationships between them. Unlike a flat inventory list, a CMDB captures dependencies (which application runs on which server, which server depends on which storage), making it invaluable for change management, impact analysis, and troubleshooting: before you patch a host you can see every service that would be affected. A well-maintained CMDB also feeds capacity planning and end-of-life decisions.</p><h3>Warranty, Support, and Disposal</h3><p>Asset records should capture <span class='keyterm'>warranty</span> and support/maintenance status — recall that owning a license does not entitle you to vendor support unless a maintenance plan exists. As assets reach end of life, the final phase demands secure <span class='keyterm'>data sanitization</span> (wiping or physically destroying drives) before recycling or disposal, so that decommissioned hardware does not leak data. Environmental and regulatory rules often govern responsible recycling. Removing the asset from the CMDB and inventory closes the loop.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A vendor audit arrives. Because every server and its software are tracked in the <strong>CMDB</strong> with license details, you quickly produce <strong>license count validation</strong> proving installs match entitlements — except one application is over by three seats, which you remediate by truing up rather than facing penalties.</div><h3>Procurement and Capacity Planning</h3><p>The lifecycle opens with <span class='keyterm'>procurement</span>, where the sysadmin translates a defined role into a hardware specification across the four subsystems, distinguishes minimum from recommended specs, and verifies components against the OS <span class='keyterm'>HCL</span> before purchase. Procurement is informed by <span class='keyterm'>capacity planning</span> — forecasting future demand from baseline trends so the purchase has growth headroom rather than needing replacement in a year. Standardizing on known-good models simplifies spare parts, driver management, and support. As hardware arrives it is tagged and entered into inventory, beginning its tracked existence.</p><h3>License Models and Compliance</h3><p>Software is an asset too, and licensing is where asset tracking earns its keep. A <span class='keyterm'>license</span> is a legal contract governing how software may be used — how many installs or concurrent users are permitted. The exam expects familiarity with several models: <strong>subscription</strong> (cloud-hosted, billed monthly/yearly, often includes support), <strong>volume</strong> (one license covering many installs for large orgs), <strong>per-instance</strong> (one license per copy), <strong>per-seat</strong> (one per potential user), <strong>per-concurrent-user</strong> (one per simultaneous user, cheaper than per-seat), <strong>per-server</strong> (CALs limiting simultaneous client connections), <strong>per-socket</strong> (per enabled CPU socket), and <strong>per-core</strong> (per enabled core). Mixing models is common — one app per-socket, another per-core — which is exactly why a tracked inventory is essential. If an audit finds installs exceeding entitlements, the organization must <span class='keyterm'>true up</span> by purchasing the shortfall, and may face legal or financial penalties for non-compliance.</p><h3>End of Life and Secure Disposal</h3><p>As assets age into <span class='keyterm'>end of life</span>, planning shifts to replacement and workload migration before support and warranty lapse — running unsupported, unpatched hardware or software is a security liability. The final phase, <span class='keyterm'>disposal/recycling</span>, must begin with <span class='keyterm'>data sanitization</span>: securely wiping or physically destroying every storage device so decommissioned hardware cannot leak data, including drives in servers, arrays, and even printers with internal storage. Environmental and regulatory rules often govern responsible e-waste recycling. Closing the loop means removing the retired asset from both the inventory and the <strong>CMDB</strong>, keeping the records that drive every other decision accurate.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div>Know the four lifecycle phases (<strong>procurement &rarr; usage &rarr; end of life &rarr; disposal</strong>) and that a <strong>CMDB</strong> stores configuration items and their relationships. Recognize the license models (subscription, volume, per-instance/seat/concurrent-user/server/socket/core). Asset management connects to <strong>licensing compliance</strong> (count validation, true-up) and ends with secure <strong>data sanitization</strong> before disposal.</div>"}
);
SRVPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Documentation & Secure Storage", body:"<p>Objective <strong>2.7</strong> also stresses documentation, a practice woven through the entire server lifecycle — including troubleshooting, where documenting symptoms, research, and the outcome of each action is treated not as a separate final step but as a habit maintained at every phase. Good documentation lets an administrator understand the environment, prevent repeat problems, onboard new staff, satisfy auditors, and recover quickly during incidents. Many service-desk systems even require troubleshooting notes before a ticket can be closed.</p><h3>Types of Documentation</h3><table><thead><tr><th>Document</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>Runbook</span></td><td>Step-by-step procedures for routine and recovery tasks</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>Network diagram</span></td><td>Physical/logical layout of devices, links, subnets, VLANs</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>Topology / rack diagram</span></td><td>Cabling, rack-unit placement, power layout</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>Configuration baseline</span></td><td>Known-good settings and performance reference</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>Asset inventory / CMDB</span></td><td>What exists, where, and how it relates</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>SOP / policy</span></td><td>Standard operating procedures and rules</td></tr><tr><td>Change/incident records</td><td>What changed, when, by whom, with what result</td></tr></tbody></table><p>A <span class='keyterm'>runbook</span> captures the exact steps to perform an operation — a backup, a failover test, a restore, a patch deployment — so the task runs consistently regardless of who executes it, and so an on-call engineer can recover a service at 3 a.m. without guesswork. <span class='keyterm'>Network and rack diagrams</span> visualize how devices interconnect (IP addressing, gateways, VLANs, trunks, physical cabling and rack positions), which is indispensable when isolating a 'layer 3 problem' or tracing a cable. <span class='keyterm'>Baselines</span> document known-good configuration and performance so deviations are obvious. Together these create the institutional memory that survives staff turnover.</p><h3>Keeping Documentation Accurate</h3><p>Documentation is only useful if current. Stale diagrams mislead troubleshooting and stale runbooks cause failed recoveries, so updates must be part of every change — when you reconfigure a subnet, add a VLAN, or replace a server, the docs and CMDB change with it. Version control and review cycles keep documents trustworthy.</p><h3>Secure Storage of Records</h3><p>Documentation frequently contains sensitive material — IP schemes, device inventories, account information, and especially <strong>credentials</strong> and recovery keys — making it a target. <span class='keyterm'>Secure storage</span> means protecting these records with the same rigor as production data: restrict access using least-privilege <strong>permissions</strong> and role-based access control; encrypt sensitive records (the source recommends enabling encryption such as EFS, BitLocker, and LUKS); store passwords and keys in a dedicated <span class='keyterm'>password manager / secrets vault</span> rather than a flat file or a wiki; and keep documentation backed up and replicated so it survives the very disaster it helps you recover from. <span class='keyterm'>Electronic signatures</span> (e.g. DocuSign) may be required to acknowledge license agreements and contracts, and those signed records must also be retained securely. Access to sensitive documentation should be logged and audited so you can prove who viewed or changed it. Storing the only copy of your disaster-recovery runbook on the server it is meant to recover defeats the purpose — off-site or cloud-replicated copies are essential.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A ransomware incident encrypts a file server. Because the recovery <strong>runbook</strong> lives in an off-site, access-controlled vault — not on the affected server — the on-call admin follows documented steps, restores from validated backups, and references the current <strong>network diagram</strong> to re-point clients, all without the original engineer present.</div><h3>Documentation Across the Lifecycle</h3><p>Documentation is not a phase that happens at the end — it accompanies every stage of the server lifecycle. During procurement it records specifications and HCL verification; during deployment it captures the configuration baseline and initial diagrams; during operation it logs changes, incidents, and patches; and during disposal it records sanitization and decommission. In troubleshooting it runs continuously: you document the symptom, your research into causes, and the result of each plan-of-action step, whether that step succeeded or failed. This running record turns isolated incidents into institutional knowledge that prevents repeat problems and accelerates the next investigation. Many ticketing systems enforce this by refusing to close a ticket until the troubleshooting notes are entered.</p><h3>Diagrams, Runbooks, and Baselines Working Together</h3><p>The three pillars reinforce one another. A <span class='keyterm'>network diagram</span> shows the logical layout — IP subnets, VLANs, trunks, gateways — while a <span class='keyterm'>rack diagram</span> shows the physical reality of cabling, rack-unit positions, and power. When someone reports a 'layer 3 problem,' the network diagram tells you which router and subnet to examine; when a drive fails, the rack diagram tells you exactly which slot to pull. A <span class='keyterm'>runbook</span> then provides the ordered steps to act — failover, restore, patch — so the task executes consistently regardless of who is on call, even at 3 a.m. without the original engineer. The <span class='keyterm'>baseline</span> supplies the known-good reference that tells you whether the system has returned to normal after the work. Together they answer where, how, and 'is it fixed yet?'</p><h3>Keeping Records Trustworthy and Auditable</h3><p>Stale documentation is worse than none because it actively misleads. Every change — a new VLAN, a re-IP'd subnet, a replaced server — must update the diagrams, runbooks, and CMDB in lockstep, ideally under version control with periodic review so the record stays trustworthy. Access to sensitive documentation should be logged and audited so you can prove who viewed or altered it, which matters both for security investigations and for regulatory compliance. <span class='keyterm'>Electronic signatures</span> (e.g. DocuSign) are often required to acknowledge license agreements and contracts, and those signed records must be retained securely alongside the operational documentation. Auditability and accuracy are what make documentation a reliable foundation rather than a liability.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam Tip</div>Documentation is continuous, not a final step. Know <strong>runbooks</strong> (procedures), <strong>diagrams</strong> (network/rack layout), and <strong>baselines</strong> (known-good reference). Store sensitive records with <strong>least-privilege permissions, encryption, a secrets vault, and off-site backups</strong> — never the only copy on the system it protects. Keep records current and <strong>audited</strong>.</div>"}
);
